Loke Kian Whee, Justin <br>Yang Kwang Yong, Joshua <br>Koh Wen Chii, Fiona'' || Planting Shadows (2009) || M<br>M<br>F || 1979<br>1974<br>1983 || Singapore<br>Malaysia<br>Singapore || Singapore\n|-\n| 30 || Wiyoga Muhardanto || Tangible Gallery (2012) || M || 1979 || Indonesia || Indonesia\n|-\n| 31 || Zulkifle Mahmod || Deck Journey (2012) || M || 1975 || Singapore || Singapore\n|}\n\n=== Sustainability ===\nArtists were selected for the use of energy-efficient LED lights and/or the incorporation of sustainable, recycleable and/or re-usable materials into their light artworks. Some of these artworks leveraged on alternative sources of energy such as solar, kinetic or wind in order to generate energy for the light installations.<ref>[http://www.asiaone.com/News/Latest+News/Relax/Story/A1Story20120224-329957.html Marina Bay light festival returns in March] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120419101615/http://www.asiaone.com/News/Latest+News/Relax/Story/A1Story20120224-329957.html |date=19 April 2012 }} AsiaOne. 24 February 2012</ref><ref>[http://www.artmap.tv/news_detail.aspx?id=1224 SINGAPORE. Art Installations light up Marina Bay] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131200447/http://www.artmap.tv/news_detail.aspx?id=1224 |date=31 January 2016 }} ArtMap. 13 March 2012</ref>\n\nProfessional sustainability consultants were also engaged to work with the event partners, artists, contractors and suppliers to ensure that suitable sustainable practices are incorporated to reduce energy use.<ref>[http://www.travelandbeyond.org/2012/03/08/going-green-in-singapore/ Going Green in Singapore] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120421005304/http://www.travelandbeyond.org/2012/03/08/going-green-in-singapore/ |date=21 April 2012 }} Travel and Beyond. Retrieved 12 April 2012</ref> The total energy usage for all the installations in the 2012 i Light Marina Bay festival was less than 7,000 kWh.<ref>[http://www.ilightmarinabay.sg/downloads/iLMB2012%20Post-Event%20Release.pdf Asia\u2019s first and only sustainable light art festival concludes on a high note, drawing a record 565,000 visitors and achieving significant energy savings] i Light Marina Bay. 11 April 2012</ref>\n\nThe festival also participated in Earth Hour on 31 March 2012 and all 31 featured artworks were switched off for an hour.<ref>[http://www.herworldplus.com/lifestyle/stuff-do/lifestyle-stuff-do-be-part-earth-hour Be part of Earth Hour] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402183800/http://www.herworldplus.com/lifestyle/stuff-do/lifestyle-stuff-do-be-part-earth-hour |date=2 April 2012 }} Her World Plus. 30 March 2012</ref>\n\nIn festival again featured the ''Switch Off, Turn Up'' Campaign, extending its reach beyond the Marina Bay precinct, with buildings across the island pledging their support.<ref name=\"Switch Off, Turn Up Campaign\">[http://www.ilightmarinabay.sg/switchoff_campaign.html \"Switch Off, Turn Up\" Campaign] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120414010255/http://www.ilightmarinabay.sg/switchoff_campaign.html |date=14 April 2012 }} i Light Marina Bay. Retrieved 12 April 2012</ref> The campaign saved more than 200,000 kWh, four times the energy saved in 2010.<ref name=\"Lighting-up for sustainability\"/> This equates to 100 tonnes of CO2 equivalent, enough to generate electricity for 762 4-bedroom HDB flats for three-weeks.<ref name=\"Lighting-up for sustainability\"/><ref>[https://adlibmagazine.wordpress.com/2012/04/11/ i Light Marina Bay 2012 closed on a successful note] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131200446/https://adlibmagazine.wordpress.com/2012/04/11/ |date=31 January 2016 }} Adlib Magazine Singapore. 11 April 2012</ref>\n\n47 properties that participated 2012\u2019s Switch Off, Turn Up campaign, up from 16 properties in 2010:<ref name=\"Switch Off, Turn Up Campaign\"/>\n\n== i Light Marina Bay 2014: Light+HeART ==\nThe third edition of i Light Marina Bay, themed Light+HeART, returned to Marina Bay from 7 March to 30 March 2014.  The festival showcased 28 environmentally sustainable light installations from around the world. To promote an environmentally-responsible behavior for a sustainable future, participating artists incorporated the use of recyclable materials and adopted energy-efficient lighting in the creation of their light art installations.\n\ni Light Marina Bay 2014 attracted a total of 685,000 local and international visitors over the course of the three-week period.  \nThe festival again engaged in the \u201cSwitch Off, Turn Up\u201d Campaign.  In 2014, 52 buildings committed to put in place measures to save energy during the festival period. Key developments involved include [[Marina Bay Sands]], [[Marina Bay Financial Centre]], and [[One Fullerton]]. Their participation signified their commitment to play a part in working towards a more sustainable future together. The campaign in 2014 achieved energy savings of 268,890 kWh.\n\n=== Programme ===\ni Light Marina Bay 2014 also featured a variety of complementary events and activities, such as free guided tours, educational talks and seminars, sporting activities, bazaars and culinary treats.\n\n=== Participating Artists ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name of Installation!! Name of Artist(s) !! Country \n|-\n| Beat || Arup (Singapore) || Singapore\n|-\n| The Wishing! Tree || The Living! Project || Singapore\n|-\n| iSWARM || SUTD \u2013 Thomas Schroepfer & Suranga Nanayakkara || Singapore\n|-\n| Happy Croco || Bibi || [[France]]\n|-\n| Bedazzled || Meinhardt Light Studio Pte. Ltd.|| Singapore\n|-\n| Lightscape Catcher || Arup (Shanghai) || [[China]]\n|-\n| Mimosa || Jason Bruges Studio || [[United Kingdom]]\n|-\n| #WEHEARTLIGHT || Light Collective || United Kingdom\n|-\n| Joujou-Ours || Uno Lai || [[Taiwan]]\n|-\n| Floating Hearts || Travesias De Luz || [[Spain]]\n|-\n| **Insert Caption Please || Ryf Zaini || Singapore\n|-\n| The Guardian Angels || Maro Avrabou & Dimitri Xenakis || [[Greece]] & France\n|-\n| Fool\u2019s Gold || Vertical Submarine || Singapore\n|-\n| The Pool || [[Jen Lewin]] Studio || [[United States|USA]]\n|-\n| Light Rain || Troika || United Kingdom\n|-\n| LiveLight || Oz Collective || Singapore & France\n|-\n| 3D Tic-Tac-Toe || Angela Chong & Sonny Windstrup || Singapore / [[Denmark]]\n|-\n| Scribbledribblequibble || Soh Ee Shaun, Chong Li-Chuan, Kenneth Cheong & Kashmira Kasmuri || Singapore\n|-\n| The Wheels of Industry || Twist Design || United Kingdom\n|-\n| Giant Dandelions || Olivia d\u2019Aboville || [[Philippines]] / France\n|-\n| HeartBeat City Lights || Egied Simons || [[Netherlands]]\n|-\n| Skeletal Retreat No.1 || Michael Lee || Singapore\n|-\n| CLOUD || Caitlind r.c. Brown & Wayne Garrett || [[Canada]]\n|-\n| 1.26 Singapore || Janet Echelman || USA\n|-\n| Digital Wattle || Out of the Dark || [[New Zealand]]\n|-\n| Flash || Nathan Yong with OTTO Solutions Pte. Ltd. || Singapore\n|-\n| A Land of Reverie|| Sheryl Ng & Nigel Ho || Singapore\n|-\n| Celebration of Life || Justin Lee with Dorier Asia Pte. Ltd. || Singapore & [[Switzerland]]\n|}\n\n== i Light Marina Bay 2016: In Praise of Shadows ==\nThe fourth edition of i Light Marina Bay, held from 4 to 27 March 2016, featured 25 installations.  The 2016 theme, \u201cIn Praise of Shadows\u201d, challenged the obsession that brighter is better and sought to reframe [[perception]]s of light and sustainability. A one-for-one exchange campaign of used incandescent bulbs for energy efficient LED light bulbs was run at i Light Marina Bay 2016.  The \"Switch Off, Turn Up\" Campaign held since the inception of i Light Marina Bay garnered a greater response from buildings around Marina Bay and beyond, with key developments involved including [[Marina Bay Sands]] and [[Marina Bay Financial Centre]]s.\n\n=== Installations ===\n* CYCLE HOUSE Hafiz Osman (Singapore)\n* LIGHT WALK Jen Lewin (USA)\n* CLOCKWORK STORIES NYP School of Design (Singapore)\n* GROOVE LIGHT NUS Department of Architecture (Singapore)\n* THE UNVEILED BEAUTY NYP School of Interactive & Digital Media (Singapore)\n* EMOGRAPH \"I DID IT\" Society (Latvia)\n* BOLT Jun Ong (Malaysia)\n* TORRENT Brandon Tay (Singapore)\n* MARINE CONSTELLATIONS Laughing Stars (Japan) & Lumen Artistry (Singapore)\n* SHADOW BATH Loop.pH (United Kingdom)\n* LAMPSHADE Sn\u00f8hetta (Norway)\n* ANGELS OF FREEDOM OGE Group, Gaston Zahr & Merav Eitan (Germany & Israel)\n* MOON HAZE Feng Jiacheng & Huang Yuanbei (China)\n* C'SCAPE Illuminate LD (Singapore)\n* LIGHT ORIGAMI KAZ Shirane (Japan)\n* LIGHTSCAPE PAVILION MisoSoupDesign (Taiwan)\n* TERRA.GLIMMER SP School of Architecture and the Built Environment (Singapore)\n* DANDELION Supermachine Studio (Thailand)\n* FISSURE Ong Kian Peng (Singapore)\n* THE CLOUD Kenny Hong (Singapore)\n* UNSEEN: TOUCH FIELD Alecia Neo (Singapore)\n* ODE TO THE WIND NTU School of Art, Design and Media (Singapore)\n* SONICTOWER Zulkifle Mahmod (Singapore)\n* GROUND CONTROL TO MAJOR TOM Rohan Abdullah & Stanley Yeo (Singapore)\n* WHAT A LOVING & BEAUTIFUL WORLD\u2013ARTSCIENCE MUSEUM [https://www.team-lab.net/ teamLab] (Japan)*\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{coord|1|17|04|N|103|51|21|E|type:city_region:SG|display=title}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:i Light Marina Bay}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:I Light Marina Bay}}\n[[Category:Art festivals in Singapore]]\n[[Category:Arts in Singapore]]\n[[Category:Contemporary art exhibitions]]\n[[Category:Light art]]\n", "name_user": "TheGreatSG'rean", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/I_Light_Marina_Bay"}
{"title_page": "Bill Crawley", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=April 2009}}{{Infobox person\n| name               = WIlliam B. Crawley, Jr\n| image              = https://bloximages.chicago2.vip.townnews.com/fredericksburg.com/content/tncms/assets/v3/editorial/b/9b/b9b2df84-a88c-560d-bc59-cc8bbce9bd2f/580be30898b66.image.jpg?crop=988%2C608%2C99%2C585\n| nationality        = American\n| education          = Hampden-Sydney University and University of Virginia\n| occupation         = Professor at University of Mary Washington\n| known_for          = Distinguished professor of the Great Lives program\n| notable_works      = Harry Byrd's Virginia and Centennial History of the University of Mary Washington\n}}\n\n'''William B. Crawley, Jr.''' is a Distinguished Professor of History and Historian at the [[University of Mary Washington]] in [[Fredericksburg, Virginia]]. He is the director of the Great Lives program.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.umw.edu/directory/employee/william-crawley/|title=William Crawley (wcrawley)|website=Directory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-16}}</ref> As well as teaching the course Great Lives: Biographical Approaches to History and Culture.<ref name=\":0\" /> His primary teaching fields are recent American history and history of the South.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://cas.umw.edu/historyamericanstudies/faculty/william-b-crawley/|title=William B. Crawley|date=2011-09-28|website=College of Arts and Sciences {{!}} History and American Studies|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-16}}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\nHe earned a B.A. in History from [[Hampden\u2013Sydney College|Hampden-Sydney college.]] As well as a M.A and a Ph. D from the University of [[Virginia]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Afterwards he went on to become a professor at the University of Mary Washington for 40 years.<ref name=\":0\" /> he earned several awards for distinguished teaching and skill in administrative positions.He is currently Distinguished Professor Emeritus of History.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 1978 he wrote ''Bill Tuck: A Political Life in Harry Byrd\u2019s Virginia'',<ref name=\":0\" /> held in several hundred libraries, according to WorldCat.<ref>http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/4004384&referer=brief_results</ref> In 1994 he received the Grellet C. Simpson Award for outstanding teaching. By 2005, the graduating seniors chose him for the Mary W. Pinschmidt Award as the professor who had the greatest impact on students\u2019 lives.<ref name=\":1\" /> In 2008 he wrote  the Centennial History of The University of Mary Washington<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Crawley, Bill}}\n[[Category:University of Mary Washington]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n\n{{US-historian-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=April 2009}}{{Infobox person\n| name               = WIlliam B. Crawley, Jr\n| image              = https://bloximages.chicago2.vip.townnews.com/fredericksburg.com/content/tncms/assets/v3/editorial/b/9b/b9b2df84-a88c-560d-bc59-cc8bbce9bd2f/580be30898b66.image.jpg?crop=988%2C608%2C99%2C585\n| nationality        = American\n| education          = Hampden-Sydney University and University of Virginia\n| occupation         = Professor at University of Mary Washington\n| known_for          = Distinguished professor of the Great Lives program\n| notable_works      = Harry Byrd's Virginia and Centennial History of the University of Mary Washington\n}}\n\n'''William B. Crawley, Jr.''' is a Distinguished Professor of History and Historian at the [[University of Mary Washington]] in [[Fredericksburg, Virginia]]. He is the director of the Great Lives program.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.umw.edu/directory/employee/william-crawley/|title=William Crawley (wcrawley)|website=Directory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-16}}</ref> As well as teaching the course Great Lives: Biographical Approaches to History and Culture. <ref name=\":0\" /> His primary teaching fields are recent American history and history of the South.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://cas.umw.edu/historyamericanstudies/faculty/william-b-crawley/|title=William B. Crawley|date=2011-09-28|website=College of Arts and Sciences {{!}} History and American Studies|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-16}}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\nHe earned a B.A. in History from [[Hampden\u2013Sydney College|Hampden-Sydney college.]] As well as a M.A and a Ph. D from the University of [[Virginia]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Afterwards he went on to become a professor at the University of Mary Washington for 40 years.<ref name=\":0\" /> he earned several awards for distinguished teaching and skill in administrative positions.He is currently Distinguished Professor Emeritus of History.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 1978 he wrote ''Bill Tuck: A Political Life in Harry Byrd\u2019s Virginia'',<ref name=\":0\" /> held in several hundred libraries, according to WorldCat.<ref>http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/4004384&referer=brief_results</ref>In 1994 he received the Grellet C. Simpson Award for outstanding teaching. By 2005, the graduating seniors chose him for the Mary W. Pinschmidt Award as the professor who had the greatest impact on students\u2019 lives.<ref name=\":1\" /> In 2008 he wrote  the Centennial History of The University of Mary Washington<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Crawley, Bill}}\n[[Category:University of Mary Washington]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n\n{{US-historian-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bill_Crawley"}
{"title_page": "The Shires (duo)", "text_new": "{{short description|British country music duo}}\n{{EngvarB|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name            = The Shires\n| image           = The Shires, Towersey 2018.jpg\n| caption         = Performing at [[Towersey Festival]], 2018\n| landscape       = true\n| background      = group_or_band\n| origin          = [[Hertfordshire]] and [[Bedfordshire]], England, UK\n| genre           = [[Country music|Country]], [[country pop]]\n| label           = [[Decca Records|Decca]], [[Universal Music Group Nashville]], [[Dot Records|Dot]], [[BMG Rights Management]]\n| years_active    = 2013\u2013present\n| website         = {{url|theshiresmusic.com/}}\n| current_members = Ben Earle<br />Crissie Rhodes\n}}\n\n'''The Shires''' are a British [[country music|country]] duo composed of singer-songwriters [[Ben Earle]] and [[Crissie Rhodes]]. Earle sings vocals, plays piano and guitar, and Rhodes shares lead vocals. The duo formed in 2013 and released their debut album ''[[Brave (The Shires album)|Brave]]'' in 2015, becoming the first UK country act to chart in the Top 10 of the [[UK Albums Chart]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicweek.com/news/read/the-shires-become-first-uk-country-act-to-reach-albums-chart-top-10/061094|title=The Shires become first UK country act to reach Albums Chart Top 10|last=Stassen|first=Murray|date=9 March 2015|work=[[Music Week]]|accessdate=9 March 2015}}</ref> The group's second album, ''[[My Universe]]'', became the fastest-selling UK country album in history when it was released in October 2016.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Shires sign US record deal with man who discovered Taylor Swift|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-37797669|publisher=BBC|date=28 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nThey hail from the neighbouring counties of [[Hertfordshire]] and [[Bedfordshire]] in England. \"[[Shire]]\" is the original term for what is usually known as a county in the United Kingdom. The duo fittingly took the band name to maintain a British identity and take a small part of Britain to the United States. After playing hardly half a dozen shows together, The Shires caught the attention of [[Decca Records]], who signed them in the United Kingdom, and they secured a contract with American record label [[Universal Music Group Nashville]], thus becoming the first ever English country act to be signed to a major Nashville label.<ref name=\"The Sunday Times Article\">[http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/culture/music/article1405270.ece The Sunday Times: That British twang, Country is being reborn in Bedford, not Nashville]. Retrieved 12 May 2014, published by Paul Sexton, 4 May 2014</ref><ref name=\"Sounds Like Nashville\">[http://www.soundslikenashville.com/artist/the-shires/ Sounds Like Nashville Artist Profile Page] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140513042522/http://www.soundslikenashville.com/artist/shires/ |date=13 May 2014 }} Retrieved on 12 May 2014</ref><ref name=\"Bob Harris Session\">[http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p01ydp16/ Bob Harris BBC Radio 2 Live Session]. Retrieved 12 May 2014</ref> They were also the first UK country act to have a top ten album and the first to receive an award from the American [[Country Music Association Awards|Country Music Association]].\n\nEarle and Rhodes were awarded Honorary Doctorates of the Arts by the University of Bedfordshire for their services and contributions to music on 25 July 2019.\n\n==Career==\n\n===2012\u20132013: Early beginnings===\nCrissie Rhodes has performed at weddings, [[pubs]] and clubs performing songs by [[Dolly Parton]] amongst others. After joining ''[[The X Factor (UK TV series)|The X Factor]]'' in [[The X Factor (UK series 10)|2013]], she was tipped as a winner but failed to qualify out of the early rounds. Her country music influences include [[Alison Krauss]], [[Martina McBride]] and [[Faith Hill]]. Ben Earle was previously a solo artist and had supported [[K t tunstall|KT Tunstall]] on tour. Also a failed ''The X Factor'' contestant, and a struggling songwriter who had been writing for 10 years, he had tried to get cuts for other artists. He discovered country music in 2012 via [[Lady Antebellum]], the American Grammy Award-winning group. He cites the [[Kacey Musgraves]] album ''[[Same Trailer Different Park]]'' as a major career inspiration.<ref name=\"Bob Harris Session\" /> Earle and Rhodes met after Ben, with an aim to become part of a duo, posted a \"There must be a country singer somewhere\" message on the social media website Facebook, seeking a partner, to which Rhodes responded.<ref name=\"The Sunday Times Article\" /><ref name=\"Sounds Like Nashville\" />\n\nAs part of [[BBC Radio 2]]'s coverage of a festival, the Shires were included as a segment in a documentary titled \"''Nashville UK''\", which assessed country music's standing in the UK and, as one of its promising artists, their determination to export their British country roots to their American counterparts.<ref name=\"Nashville UK\">[http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b03y0ljc/ Nashville UK presented by Paul Sexton; first broadcast: Thursday 20 March 2014]. Retrieved 12 May 2014</ref> The Shires have composed songs with hit Nashville songwriter Steve Mcewan (Keith Urban, Tim McGraw, Carrie Underwood) and Play Productions an accomplished Swedish writing and production company, who comprise Tim Larsson, Johan Fransson and Tobias Lundgren, who have worked with [[Rascal Flatts]] and [[Celine Dion]].<ref name=\"Sounds Like Nashville\" /><ref name=\"Play Productions\">[http://www.playproduction.se/ Play Productions Homepage]. Retrieved 12 May 2014</ref>\n\n===2014\u20132015: ''Brave''===\nThey were invited to the [[C2C: Country to Country]] 2014 Festival and performed at The Town Square Pop Stage on 16 March 2014 outside the [[London O2 arena]].<ref name=\"C2C Festival\">[http://www.c2c-countrytocountry.com/line-up/pop-up-stages/the-shires/ C2C: Country to Country 2014 Festival Profile Page]. Retrieved 2014-05-12, published March 2014</ref> Their first single \"Nashville Grey Skies\" was released on 4 April 2014 and received its first airplay on the [[Bob Harris (radio)|Bob Harris]] BBC Radio 2 Country show on 3 April 2014. It was added to the BBC Radio 2 \"B\" Playlist for the week commencing 3 May 2014 and climbed to the \"A\" playlist the following week.<ref name=\"BBC Radio 2 Playlist\">[http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio2/playlist/ BBC Radio 2 Playlist]. Retrieved 2014-05-12, published 9 May 2014</ref><ref name=\"Twitter Status\">[https://twitter.com/theshiresuk/status/461591077255147520/ The Shires Twitter Comment]. Retrieved 12 May 2014, published 30 April 2014</ref><ref name=\"BBC Radio 2 Artist Page\">[https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/artists/7a98818a-28d2-4856-a183-1df6f0984c21/ BBC Radio 2 Artist Profile Page]. Retrieved 12 May 2014</ref> The song was written by Ben before visiting [[Music City USA|Music City]] which is a song about hope with a pipe dream of building, and the UK having, a country music capital of its very own.<ref name=\"Allmusic\">[http://www.allmusic.com/album/nashville-grey-skies-mw0002644298/credits/ Allmusic Artist Credits]. Retrieved 12 May 2014</ref> It takes the musicality influences from America whilst maintaining a Britishness with the song writing. It contains [[facetious]] lines such as \"Well they say it's way too cold for cut-off jeans and they won't be drinking [[moonshine]] but [[Gin and tonic|G & T's]]\" and \"We can build our own Nashville under these grey skies\".\n\nOn 21 April 2014 they travelled to Sweden and then headed to Nashville to begin preparations and record their debut album. The duo toured the UK with [[Ward Thomas (band)|Ward Thomas]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chriscountry.co.uk/the-shires-and-ward-thomas-to-co-headline-a-tour-in-november/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=7 February 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402184657/http://www.chriscountry.co.uk/the-shires-and-ward-thomas-to-co-headline-a-tour-in-november/ |archivedate=2 April 2015}}</ref> and [[Little Big Town]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theshiresmusic.com/the-shires-go-on-tour-with-little-big-town/|title=The Shires}}</ref> prior to their own headlining tour in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theshiresmusic.com/announcing-the-2015-uk-tour/|title=The Shires}}</ref> In March 2015 the duo returned to play C2C and also released their debut studio album ''[[Brave (The Shires album)|Brave]]'' on 2 March 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theshiresmusic.com/music/|title=Music \u2013 The Shires}}</ref> The album peaked at number 10 on the [[UK Albums Chart]], making The Shires the first UK country act to have an album in the top 10. In March 2016, as the most successful country music act the UK has ever had, they were invited to C2C as \"ambassadors\", introducing the acts on the pop-up stages throughout the weekend in London, playing their own sets and appearing in the arena to introduce acts performing on the Yamaha Music Stage. The Shires opened for [[The Corrs]] on their comeback tour in 2016 including shows at Birmingham's Genting Arena, Cardiff's Motorpoint Arena, Liverpool's Echo Arena, The O2 Arena London, Manchester Arena, Glasgow's SSE Hydro, Dublin's 3Arena and the SSE Arena Belfast between 19 and 29 January.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stereoboard.com/content/view/193879/9|title=The Shires To Open for the Corrs on Comeback Tour \u2013 Stereoboard|first=Huw|last=Baines}}</ref>\n\n===2016\u20132017: ''My Universe''===\nIn July 2016, The Shires announced their second studio album ''[[My Universe]]'' would be released on 30 September 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theshiresmusic.com/|title=The Shires \u2013 My Universe}}</ref> They released \"Beats to Your Rhythm\" on 29 July as the first single from the album. The second single from the album was \"My Universe\" and was released on 16 September 2016; it charted at 89 in Scotland. Online music news site, Get to the Front, reviewed the album and stated that \"musically, lyrically and vocally there is little else you could ask for in a country album.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gettothefront.co.uk/review-shires-brave/|title=Review: The Shires \u2013 'My Universe' \u2013 GetToTheFront|date=26 August 2016}}</ref> ''My Universe'' debuted at number 3 on the [[UK Albums Chart]] and became the fastest selling UK country album of all time.\n\nIn October 2016, The Shires secured a recording contract with American label [[Big Machine Label Group]] and its imprint [[Dot Records]]. The Shires said : \"We are absolutely thrilled to sign with Dot Records in the USA. The UK is our home and we are proud of our success so far, thanks to [[Decca Records]], but it's always been a massive goal for us to build our presence and make a name for ourselves in the USA.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicweek.com/labels/read/the-shires-make-uk-country-history-with-big-machine-record-deal/066376|title=The Shires make UK country history with Big Machine record deal|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 their new single \"Daddy's Little Girl\" was released, joining BBC Radio 2's playlist. It is about Crissie's late father; the video features footage of her and her dad.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/|title=Official Charts - Home of the Official UK Top 40 Charts|website=www.officialcharts.com}}</ref> On 9 March 2017, The Shires were presented with their first [[CMA Awards|CMA Award]] by [[Kristian Bush]] during the songwriters event at the [[C2C: Country to Country]] festival.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=CountryMusic|author=CMA Country Music|number=840286404521426944|date=10 March 2017|title=Country Music duo @TheShiresUK were surprised with their first CMA \ud83c\udfc6 at the #CMAsongwriters Series show in London!}}</ref>\n\n===2018\u2013present: ''Accidentally on Purpose''===\nOn 26 January 2018, The Shires announced their third studio album ''Accidentally on Purpose'' would be released on 20 April 2018 alongside a UK tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/theshiresuk/status/956834688462704641|title=The Shires on Twitter|publisher=}}</ref> On 8 March 2018, the first single from the album \"Guilty\" premiered on [[BBC Radio 2]] before being released that day.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/theshiresuk/status/971660526102155264|title=The Shires on Twitter|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nThe second single \"Accidentally on Purpose\" was released on 9 June 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/theshiresuk/status/982182711216373761|title=The Shires on Twitter|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nThe third single \"Echo\" was released on 13 July 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://yourlifeinasong.com/the-shires-announce-new-single-echo|title=The Shires New Single Echo|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Earle and Rhodes were awarded Honorary Doctorates of the Arts by the University of Bedfordshire for their services to the Arts.\n\nIn March 2020, The Shires were announced to be playing the main stage at the [[C2C: Country to Country]] festival, replacing [[Old Dominion (band)|Old Dominion]] who withdrew due to concerns over the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], making The Shires the first UK country act to perform a set on the main stage.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://c2c-countrytocountry.com/news/2020/the-shires-announced-to-replace-old-dominion-at-c2c-2020/|title=THE SHIRES ANNOUNCED TO REPLACE OLD DOMINION\u2026|last=Country|first=C2C Country To|date=2020-03-12|website=C2C Country To Country|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:12em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:16em;\"| Details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"5\"| Peak chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| [[List of music recording certifications|Certifications]]\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Official Charts Company|UK Country]]\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[UK Albums Chart|UK]]<br/><ref name=\"UK\">{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/47270/shires/|title=Shires {{!}} full Official Chart history|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[ARIA Charts|AUS]]<br/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.auspop.com.au/2017/04/aria-chart-watch-414/|title=ARIA CHART WATCH #414|publisher=auspOp|date=1 April 2017|accessdate=1 April 2017}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Official New Zealand Music Chart|NZ]]<br/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://nztop40.co.nz/chart/albums?chart=4155|title=NZ Top 40 Albums Chart|publisher=[[Recorded Music NZ]]|date=26 October 2015|accessdate=23 October 2015}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Scottish Singles and Albums Charts|SCO]]<br/><ref name=\"SCO\">Peak positions for albums in Scotland:\n* For ''Brave'': {{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/charts/scottish-albums-chart/20150308/40/|title=Chart Archive > 8 March 2015 \u2013 14 March 2015|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]}}\n* For ''My Universe'': {{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/charts/scottish-albums-chart/20161007/40/|title=Chart Archive > 07 October 2016 \u2013 13 October 2016|publisher=Official Charts Company}}\n* For ''Accidentally on Purpose'': {{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/charts/scottish-albums-chart/20170427/40/|title=Chart Archive > 27 April 2018 \u2013 3 May 2018|publisher=Official Charts Company|accessdate=28 April 2018}}\n* For ''Greatest Hits'': {{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/charts/scottish-albums-chart/20200313/40/|title=Chart Archive > 13 March 2020 \u2013 19 March 2020|publisher=Official Charts Company|accessdate=14 March 2020}}\n* For ''Good Years'': {{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/charts/scottish-albums-chart/20200320/40/|title=Chart Archive > 20 March 2020 \u2013 26 March 2020|publisher=Official Charts Company|accessdate=21 March 2020}}\n</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Brave (The Shires album)|Brave]]''\n|\n* Released: 2 March 2015\n* Label: [[Decca Records|Decca]]\n* Formats: CD, digital download\n| 1 || 10 || \u2014 || 36 || 8\n|\n* [[British Phonographic Industry|BPI]]: Gold<ref name=\"BPI\">{{cite web | url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/certified-awards/search.aspx | title=Certified Awards | publisher=[[British Phonographic Industry]] | accessdate=14 September 2014 | format=enter \"The Shires\" into the \"Keywords\" box, then select \"Search\"}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[My Universe]]''\n|\n* Released: 30 September 2016\n* Label: Decca\n* Formats: CD, [[Gramophone record|vinyl]], digital download\n| 1 || 3 || 63 || \u2014 || 2\n|\n* BPI: Gold<ref name=\"BPI\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Accidentally on Purpose (The Shires album)|Accidentally on Purpose]]''\n|\n* Released: 20 April 2018\n* Label: Decca\n* Formats: CD, digital download\n| 1 || 3 || \u2014 || \u2014 || 2\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Good Years''\n|\n* Released: 13 March 2020\n* Label: [[BMG Rights Management|BMG]] \n* Formats: CD, digital download\n| 1 || 3 || \u2014 || \u2014 || 2\n|\n|}\n\n===Compilation albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:12em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:16em;\"| Details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\"| Peak chart positions\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[UK Albums Chart|UK]]<br/><ref name=\"UK\"/>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Scottish Singles and Albums Charts|SCO]]<br/><ref name=\"SCO\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Greatest Hits''\n|\n* Released: 6 March 2020\n* Label: BMG\n* Formats: CD, Digital download\n| 52 || 9\n|}\n\n===Extended plays===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:12em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:16em;\"| Details\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''The Green Note EP''\n|\n* Released: 4 November 2014\n* Label: Decca\n* Formats: CD, digital download\n|}\n\n===Singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:1em;\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:12em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\"| SCO\n! scope=\"col\"| Album\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2014\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Nashville Grey Skies\"\n| \u2014\n| rowspan=\"6\"| ''Brave''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Tonight\"\n| \u2014\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"| 2015\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Friday Night\"\n| \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"State Lines\"\n| \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"All Over Again\"\n| 79\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"I Just Wanna Love You\"\n| \u2014\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2016\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Beats to Your Rhythm\"\n| \u2014\n| rowspan=\"3\"| ''My Universe''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"My Universe\"\n| 89\n|-\n| 2017\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Daddy's Little Girl\"\n| \u2014\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 2018\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Guilty\"\n| 77<br /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/charts/scottish-singles-chart/20180427/41/|title=Chart Archive > 27 April 2018|publisher=Official Charts Company|accessdate=28 April 2018}}</ref>\n| rowspan=\"3\"| ''Accidentally on Purpose''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Accidentally on Purpose\"\n| \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Echo\"\n| \u2014\n|-\n| 2020\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Independence Day\"\n| 85<br /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/charts/scottish-singles-chart/20200320/41/|title=Chart Archive > 20 March 2020|publisher=Official Charts Company|accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n| ''Good Years''\n|}\n\n===Music videos===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Video\n! Director\n|-\n| 2017\n| \"Daddy's Little Girl\"\n| [[Shaun Silva]]\n|-\n|}\n\n== Tours ==\n'''Headline Tour'''\n\n* [[UK Tour 2015]] (2015)\n* [[My universe tour|My Universe Tour]] (2016/17)\n* [[Accidentally on Purpose Tour]] (2018)\n\n'''Supporting'''\n\n* [[Pain Killer Tour]] ([[Little Big Town]]) (UK) (2015)\n* [[White Light Tour]] ([[The Corrs]]) (UK and Ireland) (2016)\n* [[Now Tour (Shania Twain)|Now Tour]] ([[Shania Twain]]) (UK and Ireland) (2018)\n* [[Cry Pretty Tour 360]] ([[Carrie Underwood]]) (UK) (2019)\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Association !! Category !! Nominated work !! Result\n|-\n| 2014 || rowspan=\"11\"|[[British Country Music Association]] || Horizon Act of the Year || rowspan=\"3\"|The Shires || {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\"|2015 || Entertainer of the Year || {{Won}}\n|-\n| Duo of the Year || {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Male Vocalist of the Year || Ben Earle || {{Won}}\n|-\n| Female Vocalist of the Year || Crissie Rhodes || {{Nom}}\n|-\n| UK Song of the Year || \"Made in England\" || {{Nom}}\n|-\n| UK Album of the Year || [[Brave (The Shires album)|Brave]] || {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"|2016 || Entertainer of the Year || rowspan=\"2\"|The Shires || {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Duo of the Year || {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Male Vocalist of the Year || Ben Earle || {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Female Vocalist of the Year || Crissie Rhodes || {{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\"| 2017 || [[Country Music Association]] || [[Country Music Association Award for International Achievement|Jeff Walker Global Achievement Award]] || rowspan=\"3\"|The Shires || {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"7\"|British Country Music Association || Entertainer of the Year || {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Duo of the Year || {{Won}}\n|- \n| UK Album of the Year || [[My Universe]] || {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Video of the Year || \"My Universe\" || {{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=3| 2018\n| Duo of the Year || The Shires || {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Album of the Year || ''[[Accidentally on Purpose (The Shires album)|Accidentally on Purpose]]'' || {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Video of the Year || \"Guilty\" || {{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=1| 2019 || British Country Music Association \n| Duo of the Year || The Shires || {{Nom}}\n|-\n| 2020\n| [[Country Music Association Awards|Country Music Association]]\n| [[Country Music Association Award for International Achievement|International Broadcaster of the Year Award]]\n| Ben Earle\n| {{Won}}\n|}\n\n==Live radio appearances==\nThe Shires made their national radio debut on 1 May 2014 with a recorded live session with [[Bob Harris (radio)|Bob Harris]] OBE on BBC Radio 2. They performed 2 songs \"Brave\" and \"Only Midnight\".<ref name=autogenerated1>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b03zdgq1   Bob Harris Country BBC Radio 2 playlist]. Retrieved 2014-05-12, published 3 April 2014</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.theshiresmusic.com/ Official website]\n{{Allmusic | id= the-shires-mn0003241391| label= The Shires}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shires, The}}\n[[Category:Country music duos]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2013]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English musical duos]]\n[[Category:English country music groups]]\n[[Category:Decca Records artists]]\n[[Category:Universal Music Group artists]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British country music duo}}\n{{EngvarB|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name            = The Shires\n| image           = The Shires, Towersey 2018.jpg\n| caption         = Performing at [[Towersey Festival]], 2018\n| landscape       = true\n| background      = group_or_band\n| origin          = [[Hertfordshire]] and [[Bedfordshire]], England, UK\n| genre           = [[Country music|Country]], [[country pop]]\n| label           = [[Decca Records|Decca]], [[Universal Music Group Nashville]], [[Dot Records|Dot]], [[BMG Rights Management]]\n| years_active    = 2013\u2013present\n| website         = {{url|theshiresmusic.com/}}\n| current_members = Ben Earle<br />Crissie Rhodes\n}}\n\n'''The Shires''' are a British [[country music|country]] duo composed of singer-songwriters [[Ben Earle]] and [[Crissie Rhodes]]. Earle sings vocals, plays piano and guitar, and Rhodes shares lead vocals. The duo formed in 2013 and released their debut album ''[[Brave (The Shires album)|Brave]]'' in 2015, becoming the first UK country act to chart in the Top 10 of the [[UK Albums Chart]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicweek.com/news/read/the-shires-become-first-uk-country-act-to-reach-albums-chart-top-10/061094|title=The Shires become first UK country act to reach Albums Chart Top 10|last=Stassen|first=Murray|date=9 March 2015|work=[[Music Week]]|accessdate=9 March 2015}}</ref> The group's second album, ''[[My Universe]]'', became the fastest-selling UK country album in history when it was released in October 2016.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Shires sign US record deal with man who discovered Taylor Swift|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-37797669|publisher=BBC|date=28 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nThey hail from the neighbouring counties of [[Hertfordshire]] and [[Bedfordshire]] in England. \"[[Shire]]\" is the original term for what is usually known as a county in the United Kingdom. The duo fittingly took the band name to maintain a British identity and take a small part of Britain to the United States. After playing hardly half a dozen shows together, The Shires caught the attention of [[Decca Records]], who signed them in the United Kingdom, and they secured a contract with American record label [[Universal Music Group Nashville]], thus becoming the first ever English country act to be signed to a major Nashville label.<ref name=\"The Sunday Times Article\">[http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/culture/music/article1405270.ece The Sunday Times: That British twang, Country is being reborn in Bedford, not Nashville]. Retrieved 12 May 2014, published by Paul Sexton, 4 May 2014</ref><ref name=\"Sounds Like Nashville\">[http://www.soundslikenashville.com/artist/the-shires/ Sounds Like Nashville Artist Profile Page] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140513042522/http://www.soundslikenashville.com/artist/shires/ |date=13 May 2014 }} Retrieved on 12 May 2014</ref><ref name=\"Bob Harris Session\">[http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p01ydp16/ Bob Harris BBC Radio 2 Live Session]. Retrieved 12 May 2014</ref> They were also the first UK country act to have a top ten album and the first to receive an award from the American [[Country Music Association Awards|Country Music Association]].\n\nEarle and Rhodes were awarded Honorary Doctorates of the Arts by the University of Bedfordshire for their services and contributions to music on 25 July 2019.\n\n==Career==\n\n===2012\u20132013: Early beginnings===\nCrissie Rhodes has performed at weddings, [[pubs]] and clubs performing songs by [[Dolly Parton]] amongst others. After joining ''[[The X Factor (UK TV series)|The X Factor]]'' in [[The X Factor (UK series 10)|2013]], she was tipped as a winner but failed to qualify out of the early rounds. Her country music influences include [[Alison Krauss]], [[Martina McBride]] and [[Faith Hill]]. Ben Earle was previously a solo artist and had supported [[K t tunstall|KT Tunstall]] on tour. Also a failed ''The X Factor'' contestant, and a struggling songwriter who had been writing for 10 years, he had tried to get cuts for other artists. He discovered country music in 2012 via [[Lady Antebellum]], the American Grammy Award-winning group. He cites the [[Kacey Musgraves]] album ''[[Same Trailer Different Park]]'' as a major career inspiration.<ref name=\"Bob Harris Session\" /> Earle and Rhodes met after Ben, with an aim to become part of a duo, posted a \"There must be a country singer somewhere\" message on the social media website Facebook, seeking a partner, to which Rhodes responded.<ref name=\"The Sunday Times Article\" /><ref name=\"Sounds Like Nashville\" />\n\nAs part of [[BBC Radio 2]]'s coverage of a festival, the Shires were included as a segment in a documentary titled \"''Nashville UK''\", which assessed country music's standing in the UK and, as one of its promising artists, their determination to export their British country roots to their American counterparts.<ref name=\"Nashville UK\">[http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b03y0ljc/ Nashville UK presented by Paul Sexton; first broadcast: Thursday 20 March 2014]. Retrieved 12 May 2014</ref> The Shires have composed songs with hit Nashville songwriter Steve Mcewan (Keith Urban, Tim McGraw, Carrie Underwood) and Play Productions an accomplished Swedish writing and production company, who comprise Tim Larsson, Johan Fransson and Tobias Lundgren, who have worked with [[Rascal Flatts]] and [[Celine Dion]].<ref name=\"Sounds Like Nashville\" /><ref name=\"Play Productions\">[http://www.playproduction.se/ Play Productions Homepage]. Retrieved 12 May 2014</ref>\n\n===2014\u20132015: ''Brave''===\nThey were invited to the [[C2C: Country to Country]] 2014 Festival and performed at The Town Square Pop Stage on 16 March 2014 outside the [[London O2 arena]].<ref name=\"C2C Festival\">[http://www.c2c-countrytocountry.com/line-up/pop-up-stages/the-shires/ C2C: Country to Country 2014 Festival Profile Page]. Retrieved 2014-05-12, published March 2014</ref> Their first single \"Nashville Grey Skies\" was released on 4 April 2014 and received its first airplay on the [[Bob Harris (radio)|Bob Harris]] BBC Radio 2 Country show on 3 April 2014. It was added to the BBC Radio 2 \"B\" Playlist for the week commencing 3 May 2014 and climbed to the \"A\" playlist the following week.<ref name=\"BBC Radio 2 Playlist\">[http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio2/playlist/ BBC Radio 2 Playlist]. Retrieved 2014-05-12, published 9 May 2014</ref><ref name=\"Twitter Status\">[https://twitter.com/theshiresuk/status/461591077255147520/ The Shires Twitter Comment]. Retrieved 12 May 2014, published 30 April 2014</ref><ref name=\"BBC Radio 2 Artist Page\">[https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/artists/7a98818a-28d2-4856-a183-1df6f0984c21/ BBC Radio 2 Artist Profile Page]. Retrieved 12 May 2014</ref> The song was written by Ben before visiting [[Music City USA|Music City]] which is a song about hope with a pipe dream of building, and the UK having, a country music capital of its very own.<ref name=\"Allmusic\">[http://www.allmusic.com/album/nashville-grey-skies-mw0002644298/credits/ Allmusic Artist Credits]. Retrieved 12 May 2014</ref> It takes the musicality influences from America whilst maintaining a Britishness with the song writing. It contains [[facetious]] lines such as \"Well they say it's way too cold for cut-off jeans and they won't be drinking [[moonshine]] but [[Gin and tonic|G & T's]]\" and \"We can build our own Nashville under these grey skies\".\n\nOn 21 April 2014 they travelled to Sweden and then headed to Nashville to begin preparations and record their debut album. The duo toured the UK with [[Ward Thomas (band)|Ward Thomas]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chriscountry.co.uk/the-shires-and-ward-thomas-to-co-headline-a-tour-in-november/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=7 February 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402184657/http://www.chriscountry.co.uk/the-shires-and-ward-thomas-to-co-headline-a-tour-in-november/ |archivedate=2 April 2015}}</ref> and [[Little Big Town]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theshiresmusic.com/the-shires-go-on-tour-with-little-big-town/|title=The Shires}}</ref> prior to their own headlining tour in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theshiresmusic.com/announcing-the-2015-uk-tour/|title=The Shires}}</ref> In March 2015 the duo returned to play C2C and also released their debut studio album ''[[Brave (The Shires album)|Brave]]'' on 2 March 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theshiresmusic.com/music/|title=Music \u2013 The Shires}}</ref> The album peaked at number 10 on the [[UK Albums Chart]], making The Shires the first UK country act to have an album in the top 10. In March 2016, as the most successful country music act the UK has ever had, they were invited to C2C as \"ambassadors\", introducing the acts on the pop-up stages throughout the weekend in London, playing their own sets and appearing in the arena to introduce acts performing on the Yamaha Music Stage. The Shires opened for [[The Corrs]] on their comeback tour in 2016 including shows at Birmingham's Genting Arena, Cardiff's Motorpoint Arena, Liverpool's Echo Arena, The O2 Arena London, Manchester Arena, Glasgow's SSE Hydro, Dublin's 3Arena and the SSE Arena Belfast between 19 and 29 January.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stereoboard.com/content/view/193879/9|title=The Shires To Open for the Corrs on Comeback Tour \u2013 Stereoboard|first=Huw|last=Baines}}</ref>\n\n===2016\u20132017: ''My Universe''===\nIn July 2016, The Shires announced their second studio album ''[[My Universe]]'' would be released on 30 September 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theshiresmusic.com/|title=The Shires \u2013 My Universe}}</ref> They released \"Beats to Your Rhythm\" on 29 July as the first single from the album. The second single from the album was \"My Universe\" and was released on 16 September 2016; it charted at 89 in Scotland. Online music news site, Get to the Front, reviewed the album and stated that \"musically, lyrically and vocally there is little else you could ask for in a country album.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gettothefront.co.uk/review-shires-brave/|title=Review: The Shires \u2013 'My Universe' \u2013 GetToTheFront|date=26 August 2016}}</ref> ''My Universe'' debuted at number 3 on the [[UK Albums Chart]] and became the fastest selling UK country album of all time.\n\nIn October 2016, The Shires secured a recording contract with American label [[Big Machine Label Group]] and its imprint [[Dot Records]]. The Shires said : \"We are absolutely thrilled to sign with Dot Records in the USA. The UK is our home and we are proud of our success so far, thanks to [[Decca Records]], but it's always been a massive goal for us to build our presence and make a name for ourselves in the USA.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicweek.com/labels/read/the-shires-make-uk-country-history-with-big-machine-record-deal/066376|title=The Shires make UK country history with Big Machine record deal|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 their new single \"Daddy's Little Girl\" was released, joining BBC Radio 2's playlist. It is about Crissie's late father; the video features footage of her and her dad.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/|title=Official Charts - Home of the Official UK Top 40 Charts|website=www.officialcharts.com}}</ref> On 9 March 2017, The Shires were presented with their first [[CMA Awards|CMA Award]] by [[Kristian Bush]] during the songwriters event at the [[C2C: Country to Country]] festival.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=CountryMusic|author=CMA Country Music|number=840286404521426944|date=10 March 2017|title=Country Music duo @TheShiresUK were surprised with their first CMA \ud83c\udfc6 at the #CMAsongwriters Series show in London!}}</ref>\n\n===2018\u2013present: ''Accidentally on Purpose''===\nOn 26 January 2018, The Shires announced their third studio album ''Accidentally on Purpose'' would be released on 20 April 2018 alongside a UK tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/theshiresuk/status/956834688462704641|title=The Shires on Twitter|publisher=}}</ref> On 8 March 2018, the first single from the album \"Guilty\" premiered on [[BBC Radio 2]] before being released that day.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/theshiresuk/status/971660526102155264|title=The Shires on Twitter|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nThe second single \"Accidentally on Purpose\" was released on 9 June 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/theshiresuk/status/982182711216373761|title=The Shires on Twitter|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nThe third single \"Echo\" was released on 13 July 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://yourlifeinasong.com/the-shires-announce-new-single-echo|title=The Shires New Single Echo|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Earle and Rhodes were awarded Honorary Doctorates of the Arts by the University of Bedfordshire for their services to the Arts.\n\nIn March 2020, The Shires were announced to be playing the main stage at the [[C2C: Country to Country]] festival, replacing [[Old Dominion (band)|Old Dominion]] who withdrew due to concerns over the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], making The Shires the first UK country act to perform a set on the main stage.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://c2c-countrytocountry.com/news/2020/the-shires-announced-to-replace-old-dominion-at-c2c-2020/|title=THE SHIRES ANNOUNCED TO REPLACE OLD DOMINION\u2026|last=Country|first=C2C Country To|date=2020-03-12|website=C2C Country To Country|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:12em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:16em;\"| Details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"5\"| Peak chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| [[List of music recording certifications|Certifications]]\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Official Charts Company|UK Country]]\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[UK Albums Chart|UK]]<br/><ref name=\"UK\">{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/47270/shires/|title=Shires {{!}} full Official Chart history|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[ARIA Charts|AUS]]<br/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.auspop.com.au/2017/04/aria-chart-watch-414/|title=ARIA CHART WATCH #414|publisher=auspOp|date=1 April 2017|accessdate=1 April 2017}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Official New Zealand Music Chart|NZ]]<br/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://nztop40.co.nz/chart/albums?chart=4155|title=NZ Top 40 Albums Chart|publisher=[[Recorded Music NZ]]|date=26 October 2015|accessdate=23 October 2015}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Scottish Singles and Albums Charts|SCO]]<br/><ref name=\"SCO\">Peak positions for albums in Scotland:\n* For ''Brave'': {{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/charts/scottish-albums-chart/20150308/40/|title=Chart Archive > 8 March 2015 \u2013 14 March 2015|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]}}\n* For ''My Universe'': {{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/charts/scottish-albums-chart/20161007/40/|title=Chart Archive > 07 October 2016 \u2013 13 October 2016|publisher=Official Charts Company}}\n* For ''Accidentally on Purpose'': {{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/charts/scottish-albums-chart/20170427/40/|title=Chart Archive > 27 April 2018 \u2013 3 May 2018|publisher=Official Charts Company|accessdate=28 April 2018}}\n* For ''Greatest Hits'': {{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/charts/scottish-albums-chart/20200313/40/|title=Chart Archive > 13 March 2020 \u2013 19 March 2020|publisher=Official Charts Company|accessdate=14 March 2020}}\n* For ''Good Years'': {{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/charts/scottish-albums-chart/20200320/40/|title=Chart Archive > 20 March 2020 \u2013 26 March 2020|publisher=Official Charts Company|accessdate=21 March 2020}}\n</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Brave (The Shires album)|Brave]]''\n|\n* Released: 2 March 2015\n* Label: [[Decca Records|Decca]]\n* Formats: CD, digital download\n| 1 || 10 || \u2014 || 36 || 8\n|\n* [[British Phonographic Industry|BPI]]: Gold<ref name=\"BPI\">{{cite web | url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/certified-awards/search.aspx | title=Certified Awards | publisher=[[British Phonographic Industry]] | accessdate=14 September 2014 | format=enter \"The Shires\" into the \"Keywords\" box, then select \"Search\"}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[My Universe]]''\n|\n* Released: 30 September 2016\n* Label: Decca\n* Formats: CD, [[Gramophone record|vinyl]], digital download\n| 1 || 3 || 63 || \u2014 || 2\n|\n* BPI: Gold<ref name=\"BPI\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Accidentally on Purpose (The Shires album)|Accidentally on Purpose]]''\n|\n* Released: 20 April 2018\n* Label: Decca\n* Formats: CD, digital download\n| 1 || 3 || \u2014 || \u2014 || 2\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Good Years''\n|\n* Released: 13 March 2020\n* Label: [[BMG Rights Management|BMG]] \n* Formats: CD, digital download\n| 1 || 3 || \u2014 || \u2014 || 2\n|\n|}\n\n===Compilation albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:12em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:16em;\"| Details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\"| Peak chart positions\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[UK Albums Chart|UK]]<br/><ref name=\"UK\"/>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Scottish Singles and Albums Charts|SCO]]<br/><ref name=\"SCO\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Greatest Hits''\n|\n* Released: 6 March 2020\n* Label: BMG\n* Formats: CD, Digital download\n| 52 || 9\n|}\n\n===Extended plays===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:12em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:16em;\"| Details\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''The Green Note EP''\n|\n* Released: 4 November 2014\n* Label: Decca\n* Formats: CD, digital download\n|}\n\n===Singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:1em;\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:12em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\"| SCO\n! scope=\"col\"| Album\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2014\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Nashville Grey Skies\"\n| \u2014\n| rowspan=\"6\"| ''Brave''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Tonight\"\n| \u2014\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"| 2015\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Friday Night\"\n| \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"State Lines\"\n| \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"All Over Again\"\n| 79\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"I Just Wanna Love You\"\n| \u2014\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2016\n! scope=\"row\"| \"