{"title_page": "Bolton Corney", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n'''Bolton Corney''' (1784\u20131870) was an English army officer and official, known as a critic and antiquary.\n \n==Life==\nCorney was born at [[Greenwich]] on 28 April 1784, and baptised in the parish church of St. Alphage. He obtained in 1803 a commission as ensign in the [[28th Foot]]. Later he was at Greenwich, where he held the post of first clerk in the steward's department at the [[Greenwich Hospital, London|Royal Hospital]]. He retired in 1845 or 1846, when he married, and moved to [[Barnes, Surrey]], where he lived to his death on 30 August 1870, surrounded by his books.<ref name=\"DNB\">{{cite DNB|wstitle=Corney, Bolton|volume=12}}</ref>\n\nCorney was a member of the council of the [[Shakspere Society]] and the [[Camden Society]], and an auditor of the [[Royal Literary Fund]]. He engaged in controversy with [[Anthony Panizzi]] of the [[British Museum]].<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\n==Works==\nCorney's works were:<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\n* ''Researches and Conjectures on the Bayeux Tapestry'' [Greenwich, 1836], London 1838. He contended that the tapestry was not executed till 1205, and his view was adopted by [[John Lingard]]. \u00c9douard Lambert (1794\u20131870) published a reply to Corney, ''R\u00e9futation des objections faites contre l'antiquit\u00e9 de la Tapisserie de Bayeux'',\u2019 Bayeux, 1841.\n* ''Curiosities of Literature by I. D'Israeli illustrated'', Greenwich [1837], criticism of [[Isaac D'Israeli]] who replied in ''The Illustrator illustrated'' [1838], prompting Corney to bring out a second edition, with ''Ideas on Controversy, deduced from the practice of a Veteran; and adapted to the meanest capacity''.\n* ''On the new General Biographical Dictionary: a Specimen of Amateur Criticism, in letters to Mr. Sylvanus Urban'', Lond. 1839, privately printed. Letters originally published in the ''Gentleman's Magazine'', criticising the work of [[Hugh James Rose]].\n* ''Comments on the Evidence of Antonio Panizzi, Esq., before the Select Committee of the House of Commons on the British Museum, A.D. 1860''; privately printed. \n* ''The Sonnets of William Shakspere: a Critical Disquisition suggested by a recent discovery\u2019 (by V. E. Philar\u00e8te Chasles, relating to the inscription which precedes the sonnets in the edition of 1609) [Lond. 1862]; privately printed. \n*''An Argument on the assumed Birthday of Shakspere: reduced to shape'', 1864; privately printed.\n\nHe edited:<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\n* From manuscript ''An Essay on Landscape Gardening'' by [[Sir John Dalrymple, 4th Baronet]], Greenwich, 1823; \n* ''[[The Seasons (Thomson)|The Seasons]]'' by James Thomson, with illustrations designed by [[The Etching Club]], 1842; \n* [[Oliver Goldsmith]]'s ''Poetical Works, illustrated, with a Memoir'', 1846; \n* ''The Voyage of Sir Henry Middleton to Bantam and the Maluco Islands in 1604'' (for the [[Hakluyt Society]]), 1855; \n* ''Of the Conduct of the Understanding, by John Locke'', 1859.\n\nCorney was a contributor to ''[[Notes and Queries]]'' and ''[[Athenaeum (British magazine)|The Athen\u00e6um]]''; and he made collections on [[William Caxton]], which he provided to [[William Blades]].<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\n==Family==\nAround 1846 Corney married Henrietta Mary Pridham, eldest daughter of Richard Pridham R.N. of [[Plymouth]]. He left an only son, Bolton Glanvill Corney, born 1851, of the Royal College of Surgeons, who was appointed government medical officer in Fiji.<ref name=\"ODNB\">{{cite ODNB|id=6330|first=Clare L.|last=Taylor|title=Corney, Bolton}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n;Attribution\n{{DNB|wstitle=Corney, Bolton|volume=12}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:DNB}}\n[[Category:1784 births]]\n[[Category:1870 deaths]]\n[[Category:British Army officers]]\n[[Category:English writers]]\n[[Category:English antiquarians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n'''Bolton Corney''' (1784\u20131870) was an English army officer and official, known as a critic and antiquary.\n \n==Life==\nCorney was born at [[Greenwich]] on 28 April 1784, and baptised in the parish church of St. Alphage. He obtained in 1803 a commission as ensign in the [[28th Foot]]. Later he was at Greenwich, where he held the post of first clerk in the steward's department at the [[Greenwich Hospital, London|Royal Hospital]]. He retired in 1845 or 1846, when he married, and moved to [[Barnes, Surrey]], where he lived to his death on 30 August 1870, surrounded by his books.<ref name=\"DNB\">{{cite DNB|wstitle=Corney, Bolton|volume=12}}</ref>\n\nCorney was a member of the council of the [[Shakspere Society]] and the [[Camden Society]], and an auditor of the [[Royal Literary Fund]]. He engaged in controversy with [[Anthony Panizzi]] of the [[British Museum]].<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\n==Works==\nCorney's works were:<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\n* ''Researches and Conjectures on the Bayeux Tapestry'' [Greenwich, 1836], London 1838. He contended that the tapestry was not executed till 1205, and his view was adopted by [[John Lingard]]. \u00c9douard Lambert (1794\u20131870) published a reply to Corney, ''R\u00e9futation des objections faites contre l'antiquit\u00e9 de la Tapisserie de Bayeux'',\u2019 Bayeux, 1841.\n* ''Curiosities of Literature by I. D'Israeli illustrated'', Greenwich [1837], criticism of [[Isaac D'Israeli]] who replied in ''The Illustrator illustrated'' [1838], prompting Corney to bring out a second edition, with ''Ideas on Controversy, deduced from the practice of a Veteran; and adapted to the meanest capacity''.\n* ''On the new General Biographical Dictionary: a Specimen of Amateur Criticism, in letters to Mr. Sylvanus Urban'', Lond. 1839, privately printed. Letters originally published in the ''Gentleman's Magazine'', criticising the work of [[Hugh James Rose]].\n* ''Comments on the Evidence of Antonio Panizzi, Esq., before the Select Committee of the House of Commons on the British Museum, A.D. 1860''; privately printed. \n* ''The Sonnets of William Shakspere: a Critical Disquisition suggested by a recent discovery\u2019 (by V. E. Philar\u00e8te Chasles, relating to the inscription which precedes the sonnets in the edition of 1609) [Lond. 1862]; privately printed. \n*''An Argument on the assumed Birthday of Shakspere: reduced to shape'', 1864; privately printed.\n\nHe edited:<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\n* From manuscript ''An Essay on Landscape Gardening'' by [[Sir John Dalrymple, 4th Baronet]], Greenwich, 1823; \n* ''[[The Seasons (Thomson)|The Seasons]]'' by James Thomson, with illustrations designed by [[The Etching Club]], 1842; \n* [[Oliver Goldsmith]]'s ''Poetical Works, illustrated, with a Memoir'', 1846; \n* ''The Voyage of Sir Henry Middleton to Bantam and the Maluco Islands in 1604'' (for the [[Hakluyt Society]]), 1855; \n* ''Of the Conduct of the Understanding, by John Locke'', 1859.\n\nCorney was a contributor to ''[[Notes and Queries]]'' and ''[[Athenaeum (British magazine)|The Athen\u00e6um]]''; and he made collections on [[William Caxton]], which he provided to [[William Blades]].<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\n==Family==\nAround 1846 Corney married Henrietta Mary Pridham, eldest daughter of Richard Pridham R.N. of [[Plymouth]]. He left an only son, Bolton Glanvill Corney, born 1851, of the Royal College of Surgeons, who was appointed government medical officer in Fiji.<ref name=\"ODNB\">{{cite ODNB|id=6330|first=Clare L.|last=Taylor|title=Corney, Bolton}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n;Attribution\n{{DNB|wstitle=Corney, Bolton|volume=12}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:DNB}}\n[[Category:1784 births]]\n[[Category:1870 deaths]]\n[[Category:British Army officers]]\n[[Category:English writers]]\n[[Category:English antiquarians]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bolton_Corney"}
{"title_page": "Sanjay Gangwani", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Sanjay Gangwani\n| honorific-suffix = Dr. \n| birth_date = 16-08-1979 <ref>http://www.pas.gov.pk/index.php/members/profile/en/32/718</ref>\n| birth_place = Karachi <ref>http://www.pas.gov.pk/index.php/members/profile/en/32/718</ref>\n| office = Member of the [[Provincial Assembly of Sindh]]\n| term_start = 2018\n| term end =\n|constituency= [[DHA, Karachi]],[[Provincial Assembly of Sindh]]\n|nationality = Pakistani\n|party = [[Pakistan Tehreek-e-Insaf]]\n|children = 2 <ref>http://www.pas.gov.pk/index.php/members/profile/en/32/718</ref>\n|relations = Married <ref>http://www.pas.gov.pk/index.php/members/profile/en/32/718</ref>\n\n}}\n\n'''Sanjay Gangwani''' ({{lang-ur|{{nq|\u0633\u0646\u062c\u06d2 \u06af\u0646\u06af\u0648\u0627\u0646\u06cc}}}}) is a Pakistani politician who is an elected member of the [[Provincial Assembly of Sindh]] and a close associate of [[Imran khan]]. He is the son of a technocrat, Engr. Dr. Murlidhar. P. Gangwani, who in his career span of 37 years has served as the Chairman of SCCP,<ref>https://fp.brecorder.com/2005/08/20050811310826/</ref> President of (FEISCA) Federation of Engineering Institutions of South and Central Asia,<ref>http://www.ptj.com.pk/Web%202004/03-2004/textile_engineering.html</ref> President of IEP (Institution of Engineers Pakistan), Board of Director at [[World Federation of Engineering Organizations]], Chairman (SAARC) [[South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation]] Engineering Council, Board of Director at [[Institute of Industrial and Systems Engineers]], Board of Governor [[Lahore University of Management Sciences]], Board of Director (Pakistan Engineering Congress), Board of Advisory (IMechE) [[Institution of Mechanical Engineers]], Patron-in-Chief (Quaid-e-Azam Forum Institute of Engineers), Board of Governor [[PIMSAT]], Board of Governor [[University of EAST]], Board of Governor [[Institute of Business Administration, Karachi]], Board of Director  (IChemE) [[Institution of Chemical Engineers]]  and Convener of [[Pakistan Engineering Council]]. Engr. Dr. M.P. Gangwani was a highly decorated officer and known as the man of crisis in the government of Pakistan and rose to be the only Non-Muslim to serve on the highest grade in the Civil Service of Pakistan, retired on grade '''22''' and conducted in the [[Hall of Fame]] of 2009 as the Luminaries of the Land and named [[Who's Who]] of Pakistan for his outstanding achievements both in professional and social career.<ref>https://www.dawn.com/news/47910</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nDr. Sanjay Gangwani was elected to Provincial Assembly of Sindh on a reserved seat for minorities in [[2018 Pakistani general election]] representing [[Pakistan Tehreek-e-Insaf]].<ref>{{cite web |title=General Elections 2018 - Reserved Seats Returned Candidates Notifications - National Assembly and Provincial Assemblies|url=https://www.ecp.gov.pk//PrintDocument.aspx?PressId=65485&type=PDF|website=Election Commission of Pakistan|accessdate=15 August 2018}}</ref> He started his political Career in 2008 and later on the influence of [[Ali Haider Zaidi]] joined [[Pakistan Tehreek-e-Insaf]] in 2011. He consider [[Ali Haider Zaidi]] and [[Arif Alvi]] his political mentors. Sanjay Gangwani is a Medical Doctor by profession, studied at [[Dow Medical College]] from where he has received his Bachelors of Surgery and Bachelors of Medicine degree.<ref>http://www.pas.gov.pk/index.php/members/profile/en/32/718</ref> He has been continuously working for the rights of minorities in Pakistan and decided to join PTI [[Pakistan Tehreek-e-Insaf]] in order to serve the nation and his people. Sanjay Gangwani has been visiting interiors to check the medical facilities for the poor and needy. Recently along with other members of PTI delegation arrived in [[Tharparkar]]  on a two-day exploratory visit. They visited different sections of Civil Hospitals at [[Umerkot]],[[Chachro]] and [[Mithi]] , and inquired about the health of the admitted children and other patients and distributed relief material. They also discussed the issues of patient care, state of medical equipment and medicine supply with the medical superintendent and other doctors.<ref>https://www.thenews.com.pk/print/370431-pti-leaders-slam-medical-facilities-in-tharparkar</ref>\nSanjay Gangwani believes patriotism is the key to protect the motherland.<ref>https://www.dawn.com/news/1466192</ref> For the outstanding contribution by the Gangwani Family, the government of Pakistan has named the road on the name of Sanjay Gangwani in [[Karachi Development Authority]] Scheme 1. Today, the road is known as Sanjay Gangwani Road.<ref>https://www.google.com/maps/place/Sanjay+Gangwani+Road,+KDA+Scheme+%231+KDA+Scheme+1,+Karachi,+Karachi+City,+Sindh,+Pakistan/data=!4m2!3m1!1s0x3eb33eb5c2acf681:0xfdb07dd4a16611af?sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjl1ZWolbLiAhUPSq0KHXMcBPoQ8gEwAHoECAkQAQ</ref> He gives the credit to this honor to his father's (Dr. Engr. M. P. Gangwani)'s unconditional contribution to the country.<ref>https://www.google.com/maps/place/Sanjay+Gangwani+Road,+KDA+Scheme+%231+KDA+Scheme+1,+Karachi,+Karachi+City,+Sindh,+Pakistan/data=!4m2!3m1!1s0x3eb33eb5c2acf681:0xfdb07dd4a16611af?sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjl1ZWolbLiAhUPSq0KHXMcBPoQ8gEwAHoECAkQAQ</ref>\n\n==Social & Charitable Causes==\nDr. Sanjay Gangwani is an active member of [[SOS Children's Villages]] and [[UNICEF]]. He believes in giving back to the society. His father was a very active social worker in Pakistan who has served as the President [[Rotary Club]],<ref>https://www.rotary.org/en</ref> President (IEP - Foundation),<ref>https://iep.com.pk/</ref> District Governor [[Lions Clubs International]],<ref>http://pakistanhindupost.blogspot.com/2009/12/mr-muralidhar-p-gangwani-mpg-lifetime.html</ref> Governor [[Rotary International]] District 3271, President of Friends Association, President of Pakistan Minority Wing, and President [[NED University of Engineering and Technology|NED]] Old Boys Association.<ref>http://pakistanhindupost.blogspot.com/2009/12/mr-muralidhar-p-gangwani-mpg-lifetime.html</ref> Following his fathers dream, Dr.Sanjay has been organizing free medical camps and seminars for the poor and needy in Pakistan. He has organized several medical camps and seminars in [[Karachi]] along with [[Arif Alvi]]. They both have helped in organizing camps which focuses on \"Eye\" emergencies in the undeveloped and rural areas of [[Sindh]], so far they have helped more than 200 eye patients with major eye surgeries for free and recently started the campaign to create awareness for heart ailments. Since, Dr. Gangwani is a certified [[cardiologist]] he has been working to organize camps and seminars for patients with heart ailments and related problems. Dr. Sanjay Gangwani is been an active member of [[Pakistan Hindu Council]]<ref>http://www.pakistanhinducouncil.org/</ref> and [[Pakistan Hindu Panchayat]]<ref>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pakistan_Hindu_Panchayat</ref> both the organizations were founded by his father.<ref>http://www.pakistanhinducouncil.org/</ref> Also, he is an avid supporter of [[Edhi Foundation]],<ref>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edhi_Foundation</ref> and [[Saylani Welfare Trust]].<ref>https://www.saylaniwelfare.com/home</ref> He is also serving as a Director of International Affairs at [[Rotary Club]].<ref>http://www.na250.com/forms/shares/new?page_id=1252</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nSanjay Gangwani is a Medical Doctor by profession, studied at [[Dow Medical College]] from where he has received his Bachelors of Surgery and Bachelors of Medicine degree. He later went to the United Kingdom for his certification of (MRCS) [[Membership of the Royal Colleges of Surgeons of Great Britain and Ireland]]. After coming back to Karachi he joined [[Dr. Ruth Pfau Hospital]]. He is married and has two children.<ref>http://www.pas.gov.pk/index.php/members/profile/en/32/718</ref> His father Engr. Dr. M.P. Gangwani was the Founder and President of [[Pakistan Hindu Council]],<ref>http://www.pakistanhinducouncil.org/</ref> Founding President of [[Pakistan Hindu Panchayat]]<ref>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pakistan_Hindu_Panchayat</ref> and Patron-in-Chief of Pak Hindu Welfare Association.<ref>http://phseva.org/</ref> Dr. Sanjay Gangwani is been an active member of [[Pakistan Hindu Council]] and [[Pakistan Hindu Panchayat]].<ref>http://www.pakistanhinducouncil.org/</ref>\n\nGangwani family is one of the most highly respectable and educated families in Pakistan. He has two younger brothers Rakesh Gangwani an alumnus of [[NED University of Engineering and Technology]],<ref>https://www.linkedin.com/in/rakeshgangwani/</ref> [[University of Indianapolis]],<ref>https://www.linkedin.com/in/rakeshgangwani/</ref> and [[Wharton School of Business]]<ref>https://www.linkedin.com/in/rakeshgangwani/</ref> and Jitesh Gangwani an alumnus of [[University of Indianapolis]],<ref>https://www.linkedin.com/in/gangwanijitesh/</ref> [[Johns Hopkins University]]<ref>https://www.linkedin.com/in/gangwanijitesh/</ref> and [[Texas A&M University]]<ref>https://www.linkedin.com/in/gangwanijitesh/</ref> both are settled in the [[United States of America]]. His father Engr. Dr. M. P. Gangwani has done his graduation in Mechanical Engineering from [[NED University of Engineering and Technology]]<ref>http://pakistanhindupost.blogspot.com/2009/12/mr-muralidhar-p-gangwani-mpg-lifetime.html</ref> and later went to [[Imperial College London]]<ref>https://www.imperial.ac.uk/engineering/</ref> and [[Kyoto University]]<ref>https://www.kyoto-u.ac.jp/en/</ref> for his Masters in [[Industrial Engineering]] and [[Heavy equipment]], and [[University of Manitoba]]<ref>http://umanitoba.ca/</ref> for his [[Doctor of Philosophy]] in [[Human Resource Management]]. Even his Grandfather Deewan Parmanand Gangwani was a [[Barrister]] who graduated from [[Bombay University]]<ref>http://mu.ac.in/portal/faculties/law/</ref> in 1946 and was a class mate of [[Ram Jethmalani]] and [[L. K. Advani]] in Shikarpur, Sindh. Deewan Parmanand Gangwani was a prominent lawyer and served as the Municipal Commissioner of District Shikarpur. Renowned Lawyer and Writer [[Shaikh Ayaz]] has discussed in details about his friendship with Deewan Parmanand Gangwani is his book [[Shah Jo Risalo]]<ref>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shah_Jo_Risalo</ref> and explained how Deewan Parmanand Gangwani was the only person used to be with him in his bad times and used to visit him while he was in exile and is one of the biggest influence in his life. Deewan Parmanad Gangwani worked in several cases along with [[A. K. Brohi]] they both were very good friends and he also discussed about his friendship with Gangwani in his book (Testament of faith). Dr. Sanjay is also serving as a Director of International Affairs at [[Rotary International]] where his father served as a Governor of District 3721.<ref>http://pakistanhindupost.blogspot.com/2009/12/mr-muralidhar-p-gangwani-mpg-lifetime.html</ref> For the outstanding contribution by the Gangwani family the government has named a road on the name of Dr. Sanjay Gangwani in [[Karachi Development Authority]]\nScheme 1 in [[Karachi]] and a public park in [[Hyderabad]] Sindh as M. P. Gangwani Park.<ref>https://www.google.com/maps/place/Sanjay+Gangwani+Road,+KDA+Scheme+%231+KDA+Scheme+1,+Karachi,+Karachi+City,+Sindh,+Pakistan/@24.8801661,67.0867655,17z/data=!3m1!4b1!4m5!3m4!1s0x3eb33eb5c2acf681:0xfdb07dd4a16611af!8m2!3d24.8801661!4d67.0889542</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gangwani, Sanjay}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Pakistan Tehreek-e-Insaf MPAs (Sindh)]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Sindh]]\n[[Category:Sindhi people]]\n[[Category:Pakistani Hindus]]\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Sanjay Gangwani\n| honorific-suffix = Dr. \n| birth_date = 16-08-1979 <ref>http://www.pas.gov.pk/index.php/members/profile/en/32/718</ref>\n| birth_place = Karachi <ref>http://www.pas.gov.pk/index.php/members/profile/en/32/718</ref>\n| office = Member of the [[Provincial Assembly of Sindh]]\n| term_start = 2018\n| term end =\n|constituency= [[DHA, Karachi]],[[Provincial Assembly of Sindh]]\n|nationality = Pakistani\n|party = [[Pakistan Tehreek-e-Insaf]]\n|children = 2 <ref>http://www.pas.gov.pk/index.php/members/profile/en/32/718</ref>\n|relations = Married <ref>http://www.pas.gov.pk/index.php/members/profile/en/32/718</ref>\n\n}}\n\n'''Sanjay Gangwani''' ({{lang-ur|{{nq|\u0633\u0646\u062c\u06d2 \u06af\u0646\u06af\u0648\u0627\u0646\u06cc}}}}) is a Pakistani politician who is an elected member of the [[Provincial Assembly of Sindh]] and a close associate of [[Imran khan]]. He is the son of a technocrat, Engr. Dr. Murlidhar. P. Gangwani, who in his career span of 37 years has served as the Chairman of SCCP,<ref>https://fp.brecorder.com/2005/08/20050811310826/</ref> President of (FEISCA) Federation of Engineering Institutions of South and Central Asia,<ref>http://www.ptj.com.pk/Web%202004/03-2004/textile_engineering.html</ref> President of IEP (Institution of Engineers Pakistan), Board of Director at [[World Federation of Engineering Organizations]], Chairman (SAARC) [[South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation]] Engineering Council, Board of Director at [[Institute of Industrial and Systems Engineers]], Board of Governor [[Lahore University of Management Sciences]], Board of Director (Pakistan Engineering Congress), Board of Advisory (IMechE) [[Institution of Mechanical Engineers]], Patron-in-Chief (Quaid-e-Azam Forum Institute of Engineers), Board of Governor [[PIMSAT]], Board of Governor [[University of EAST]], Board of Governor [[Institute of Business Administration, Karachi]], Board of Director  (IChemE) [[Institution of Chemical Engineers]]  and Convener of [[Pakistan Engineering Council]]. Engr. Dr. M.P. Gangwani was a highly decorated officer and known as the man of crisis in the government of Pakistan and rose to be the only Non-Muslim to serve on the highest grade in the Civil Service of Pakistan, retired on grade '''22''' and conducted in the [[Hall of Fame]] of 2009 as the Luminaries of the Land and named [[Who's who]] of Pakistan for his outstanding achievements both in professional and social career.<ref>https://www.dawn.com/news/47910</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nDr. Sanjay Gangwani was elected to Provincial Assembly of Sindh on a reserved seat for minorities in [[2018 Pakistani general election]] representing [[Pakistan Tehreek-e-Insaf]].<ref>{{cite web |title=General Elections 2018 - Reserved Seats Returned Candidates Notifications - National Assembly and Provincial Assemblies|url=https://www.ecp.gov.pk//PrintDocument.aspx?PressId=65485&type=PDF|website=Election Commission of Pakistan|accessdate=15 August 2018}}</ref> He started his political Career in 2008 and later on the influence of [[Ali Haider Zaidi]] joined [[Pakistan Tehreek-e-Insaf]] in 2011. He consider [[Ali Haider Zaidi]] and [[Arif Alvi]] his political mentors. Sanjay Gangwani is a Medical Doctor by profession, studied at [[Dow Medical College]] from where he has received his Bachelors of Surgery and Bachelors of Medicine degree.<ref>http://www.pas.gov.pk/index.php/members/profile/en/32/718</ref> He has been continuously working for the rights of minorities in Pakistan and decided to join PTI [[Pakistan Tehreek-e-Insaf]] in order to serve the nation and his people. Sanjay Gangwani has been visiting interiors to check the medical facilities for the poor and needy. Recently along with other members of PTI delegation arrived in [[Tharparkar]]  on a two-day exploratory visit. They visited different sections of Civil Hospitals at [[Umerkot]],[[Chachro]] and [[Mithi]] , and inquired about the health of the admitted children and other patients and distributed relief material. They also discussed the issues of patient care, state of medical equipment and medicine supply with the medical superintendent and other doctors.<ref>https://www.thenews.com.pk/print/370431-pti-leaders-slam-medical-facilities-in-tharparkar</ref>\nSanjay Gangwani believes patriotism is the key to protect the motherland.<ref>https://www.dawn.com/news/1466192</ref> For the outstanding contribution by the Gangwani Family, the government of Pakistan has named the road on the name of Sanjay Gangwani in [[Karachi Development Authority]] Scheme 1. Today, the road is known as Sanjay Gangwani Road.<ref>https://www.google.com/maps/place/Sanjay+Gangwani+Road,+KDA+Scheme+%231+KDA+Scheme+1,+Karachi,+Karachi+City,+Sindh,+Pakistan/data=!4m2!3m1!1s0x3eb33eb5c2acf681:0xfdb07dd4a16611af?sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjl1ZWolbLiAhUPSq0KHXMcBPoQ8gEwAHoECAkQAQ</ref> He gives the credit to this honor to his father's (Dr. Engr. M. P. Gangwani)'s unconditional contribution to the country.<ref>https://www.google.com/maps/place/Sanjay+Gangwani+Road,+KDA+Scheme+%231+KDA+Scheme+1,+Karachi,+Karachi+City,+Sindh,+Pakistan/data=!4m2!3m1!1s0x3eb33eb5c2acf681:0xfdb07dd4a16611af?sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjl1ZWolbLiAhUPSq0KHXMcBPoQ8gEwAHoECAkQAQ</ref>\n\n==Social & Charitable Causes==\nDr. Sanjay Gangwani is an active member of [[SOS Children's Villages]] and [[UNICEF]]. He believes in giving back to the society. His father was a very active social worker in Pakistan who has served as the President [[Rotary Club]],<ref>https://www.rotary.org/en</ref> President (IEP - Foundation),<ref>https://iep.com.pk/</ref> District Governor [[Lions Clubs International]],<ref>http://pakistanhindupost.blogspot.com/2009/12/mr-muralidhar-p-gangwani-mpg-lifetime.html</ref> Governor [[Rotary International]] District 3271, President of Friends Association, President of Pakistan Minority Wing, and President [[NED University of Engineering and Technology|NED]] Old Boys Association.<ref>http://pakistanhindupost.blogspot.com/2009/12/mr-muralidhar-p-gangwani-mpg-lifetime.html</ref> Following his fathers dream, Dr.Sanjay has been organizing free medical camps and seminars for the poor and needy in Pakistan. He has organized several medical camps and seminars in [[Karachi]] along with [[Arif Alvi]]. They both have helped in organizing camps which focuses on \"Eye\" emergencies in the undeveloped and rural areas of [[Sindh]], so far they have helped more than 200 eye patients with major eye surgeries for free and recently started the campaign to create awareness for heart ailments. Since, Dr. Gangwani is a certified [[cardiologist]] he has been working to organize camps and seminars for patients with heart ailments and related problems. Dr. Sanjay Gangwani is been an active member of [[Pakistan Hindu Council]]<ref>http://www.pakistanhinducouncil.org/</ref> and [[Pakistan Hindu Panchayat]]<ref>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pakistan_Hindu_Panchayat</ref> both the organizations were founded by his father.<ref>http://www.pakistanhinducouncil.org/</ref> Also, he is an avid supporter of [[Edhi Foundation]],<ref>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edhi_Foundation</ref> and [[Saylani Welfare Trust]].<ref>https://www.saylaniwelfare.com/home</ref> He is also serving as a Director of International Affairs at [[Rotary Club]].<ref>http://www.na250.com/forms/shares/new?page_id=1252</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nSanjay Gangwani is a Medical Doctor by profession, studied at [[Dow Medical College]] from where he has received his Bachelors of Surgery and Bachelors of Medicine degree. He later went to the United Kingdom for his certification of (MRCS) [[Membership of the Royal Colleges of Surgeons of Great Britain and Ireland]]. After coming back to Karachi he joined [[Dr. Ruth Pfau Hospital]]. He is married and has two children.<ref>http://www.pas.gov.pk/index.php/members/profile/en/32/718</ref> His father Engr. Dr. M.P. Gangwani was the Founder and President of [[Pakistan Hindu Council]],<ref>http://www.pakistanhinducouncil.org/</ref> Founding President of [[Pakistan Hindu Panchayat]]<ref>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pakistan_Hindu_Panchayat</ref> and Patron-in-Chief of Pak Hindu Welfare Association.<ref>http://phseva.org/</ref> Dr. Sanjay Gangwani is been an active member of [[Pakistan Hindu Council]] and [[Pakistan Hindu Panchayat]].<ref>http://www.pakistanhinducouncil.org/</ref>\n\nGangwani family is one of the most highly respectable and educated families in Pakistan. He has two younger brothers Rakesh Gangwani an alumnus of [[NED University of Engineering and Technology]],<ref>https://www.linkedin.com/in/rakeshgangwani/</ref> [[University of Indianapolis]],<ref>https://www.linkedin.com/in/rakeshgangwani/</ref> and [[Wharton School of Business]]<ref>https://www.linkedin.com/in/rakeshgangwani/</ref> and Jitesh Gangwani an alumnus of [[University of Indianapolis]],<ref>https://www.linkedin.com/in/gangwanijitesh/</ref> [[Johns Hopkins University]]<ref>https://www.linkedin.com/in/gangwanijitesh/</ref> and [[Texas A&M University]]<ref>https://www.linkedin.com/in/gangwanijitesh/</ref> both are settled in the [[United States of America]]. His father Engr. Dr. M. P. Gangwani has done his graduation in Mechanical Engineering from [[NED University of Engineering and Technology]]<ref>http://pakistanhindupost.blogspot.com/2009/12/mr-muralidhar-p-gangwani-mpg-lifetime.html</ref> and later went to [[Imperial College London]]<ref>https://www.imperial.ac.uk/engineering/</ref> and [[Kyoto University]]<ref>https://www.kyoto-u.ac.jp/en/</ref> for his Masters in [[Industrial Engineering]] and [[Heavy equipment]], and [[University of Manitoba]]<ref>http://umanitoba.ca/</ref> for his [[Doctor of Philosophy]] in [[Human Resource Management]]. Even his Grandfather Deewan Parmanand Gangwani was a [[Barrister]] who graduated from [[Bombay University]]<ref>http://mu.ac.in/portal/faculties/law/</ref> in 1946 and was a class mate of [[Ram Jethmalani]] and [[L. K. Advani]] in Shikarpur, Sindh. Deewan Parmanand Gangwani was a prominent lawyer and served as the Municipal Commissioner of District Shikarpur. Renowned Lawyer and Writer [[Shaikh Ayaz]] has discussed in details about his friendship with Deewan Parmanand Gangwani is his book [[Shah Jo Risalo]]<ref>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shah_Jo_Risalo</ref> and explained how Deewan Parmanand Gangwani was the only person used to be with him in his bad times and used to visit him while he was in exile and is one of the biggest influence in his life. Deewan Parmanad Gangwani worked in several cases along with [[A. K. Brohi]] they both were very good friends and he also discussed about his friendship with Gangwani in his book (Testament of faith). Dr. Sanjay is also serving as a Director of International Affairs at [[Rotary International]] where his father served as a Governor of District 3721.<ref>http://pakistanhindupost.blogspot.com/2009/12/mr-muralidhar-p-gangwani-mpg-lifetime.html</ref> For the outstanding contribution by the Gangwani family the government has named a road on the name of Dr. Sanjay Gangwani in [[Karachi Development Authority]]\nScheme 1 in [[Karachi]] and a public park in [[Hyderabad]] Sindh as M. P. Gangwani Park.<ref>https://www.google.com/maps/place/Sanjay+Gangwani+Road,+KDA+Scheme+%231+KDA+Scheme+1,+Karachi,+Karachi+City,+Sindh,+Pakistan/@24.8801661,67.0867655,17z/data=!3m1!4b1!4m5!3m4!1s0x3eb33eb5c2acf681:0xfdb07dd4a16611af!8m2!3d24.8801661!4d67.0889542</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gangwani, Sanjay}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Pakistan Tehreek-e-Insaf MPAs (Sindh)]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Sindh]]\n[[Category:Sindhi people]]\n[[Category:Pakistani Hindus]]\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n", "name_user": "Wbm1058", "label": "safe", "comment": "Spelling correction; redirect bypass fromWho's whotoWho's Whousingpopups", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sanjay_Gangwani"}
{"title_page": "Atlantic Guards", "text_new": "{{Infobox Criminal organization\n| name                = Atlantic Guards\n| image               =\n| caption             =\n| founded =  \n| founding location   = [[Bowery]], [[Manhattan]], [[New York City]]\n| founded by          = \n| years active        = 1840s-1860s\n| territory           = Bowery, Manhattan, New York City\n| ethnic makeup       = Non-Irish American\n| membership est      = ?\n| criminal activities = [[Assault]], [[street fighting]], [[knife fight]]ing\n| allies              = [[Bowery Boys]], American Guards, O'Connell Guards, True Blue Americans, [[American Republican Party (1843)|American Republican Party]] (American Nativist Party, American Party), [[Order of the Star Spangled Banner]] (Anti-immigrant secret society)\n| rivals              = [[Dead Rabbits]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Atlantic Guards''' were a 19th-century [[United States|American]] [[street gang]] active in [[New York City]] from the 1840s to the 1860s. It was one of the original, and among the most important gangs of the early days of the [[Bowery]], along with the [[Bowery Boys]], [[American Guards]], [[O'Connell Guards]], and the [[True Blue Americans]].<ref name=\"Asbury\">[[Herbert Asbury|Asbury, Herbert]]. ''The Gangs of New York: An Informal History of the New York Underworld''. New York: Alfred A. Knopf, 1928. (pg. 26-27, 102, 106) {{ISBN|1-56025-275-8}}</ref><ref name=\"Peterson\">Peterson, Virgil W. ''The Mob: 200 Years of Organized Crime in New York''. Ottawa, Illinois: Green Hill Publishers, 1983. (pg. 13) {{ISBN|0-89803-123-0}}</ref><ref name=\"Kenney\">Kenney, Dennis Jay and James O. Finckenauer. ''Organized Crime in America''. New York: Wadsworth Publishing Company, 1995. (pg. 75) {{ISBN|0-534-24702-4}}</ref>\n\nAlthough engaging in [[street fighting]], these gangs were generally less [[street gang|criminal in nature]] than their Five Point rivals, stopping \"just short of murder\",<ref>{{cite news |title=New York Cavalcade: Paid Killers and the Underworld |author=Sobol, Louis |authorlink=Louis Sobol |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=XZstAAAAIBAJ&sjid=u54FAAAAIBAJ&pg=835,3464677 |newspaper=[[Daytona Beach Morning Journal]] |date=November 18, 1965 |accessdate=October 31, 2012}}</ref> instead formed as nativist [[vigilante|vigilante groups]] focused on protecting Bowery neighborhoods.<ref name=\"Giamo\">Giamo, Benedict. ''On the Bowery: Confronting Homelessness in American Society''. Iowa City: University of Iowa Press, 1989. (pg. 9) {{ISBN|0-87745-243-1}}</ref><ref name=\"Sante\">[[Luc Sante|Sante, Luc]]. ''Low Life: Lures and Snares of Old New York''. New York: Farrar, Straus & Giroux, 2003. (pg. 200-203) {{ISBN|0-374-52899-3}}</ref> It was common for Bowery and Five Point gangs alike to imitate (and sometimes parody) actual military companies and wear signature \"uniforms\" (e.g. the [[top hat|stove pipe hats]] and long black [[frock coat]]s of the True Blue Americans).<ref name=\"Asbury\"/><ref name=\"Peterson\"/><ref name=\"Kenney\"/><ref>Kett, Joseph F. ''Rites of Passage: Adolescence in America, 1790 to the Present''. New York: Basic Books, 1977. (pg. 92) {{ISBN|0465070434}}</ref> The Atlantic Guards wore a red stripe on their trousers.<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news |title=Murderous Gangs Of A Half Century And More Ago |author= |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1912/08/04/100591919.pdf |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=August 4, 1912 |accessdate=October 31, 2012}}</ref>\n\nA longtime ally of the Bowery Boys, they were referred to by journalist [[Carleton Beals]] as \"[[William Poole|Bill \"the Butcher\" Poole]]'s [[Christopher Street]] thugs\"<ref>[[Carleton Beals|Beals, Carleton]]. ''Brass-Knuckle Crusade: The Great Know-Nothing Conspiracy, 1820-1860''. New York: Hastings House, 1960. (pg. 20)</ref> and often warred with the [[Irish American]] gangs of the [[Five Points, Manhattan|Five Points]], most especially, the [[Dead Rabbits]]. This feud would continue throughout the 1840s and 50s, at the height of the [[Know Nothing]] movement, culminating in the [[Dead Rabbits Riot]] in 1857.<ref name=\"Giamo\"/> The riot originally began with a Five Points raid on No. 42 Bowery, the headquarters of the Bowery Boys and the Atlantic Guards, in \"celebration\" of the [[Fourth of July]].<ref>{{cite news |title=The Gangs of New York: Facts That Out Thrill Fiction |author= |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=12JQAAAAIBAJ&sjid=FA8EAAAAIBAJ&pg=5184,2345188 |newspaper=[[The Milwaukee Sentinel]] |date=November 13, 1928 |accessdate=October 31, 2012}}</ref> The Five Pointers showered the saloon with sticks and paving stone before moving on to the nearby Branch Hotel. The guests managed to hold off the mob until they were driven off by an estimated 300 Atlantic Guards and Bowery Boys.<ref>Ferrara, Eric. ''The Bowery: A History of Grit, Graft and Grandeur''. Charleston, South Carolina: The History Press, 2011. (pg. 50) {{ISBN|1-60949-178-5}}</ref> Fighting continued, however, and soon escalated into a citywide gang war lasting two days before order was restored by the [[New York State Militia]] under Major-General [[Charles W. Sandford]].<ref name=\"Asbury\"/><ref name=\"Sante\"/><ref name=\"NYT\"/><ref>Mendelsohn, Joyce. ''The Lower East Side Remembered and Revisited: A History and Guide to a Legendary New York Neighborhood''. New York: Columbia University Press, 2009. (pg. 238) {{ISBN|0-231-14761-9}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n*The Atlantic Guards are referenced in the [[historical novel]]s ''Andersonville'' (1993) by [[MacKinlay Kantor]] and ''The Coming Storm'' (2011) by Dominic Lagan.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*[[Carleton Beals|Beals, Carleton]]. ''Brass-Knuckle Crusade: The Great Know-Nothing Conspiracy, 1820-1860''. New York: Hastings House, 1960.\n*Harlow, Alvin Fay. ''Old Bowery Days: The Chronicles of a Famous Street''. New York: D. Appleton, 1931.\n*Terrett, Courtenay. ''Only Saps Work: A Ballyhoo for Racketeering''. New York: The Vanguard Press, 1930.\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Atlantic Guards}}\n[[Category:Former gangs in New York City]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Criminal organization\n| name                = Atlantic Guards\n| image               =\n| caption             =\n| founded =  \n| founding location   = [[Bowery]], [[Manhattan]], [[New York City]]\n| founded by          = \n| years active        = 1840s-1860s\n| territory           = Bowery, Manhattan, New York City\n| ethnic makeup       = Non-Irish American\n| membership est      = ?\n| criminal activities = [[Assault]], [[street fighting]], [[knife fight]]ing\n| allies              = [[Bowery Boys]], American Guards, O'Connell Guards, True Blue Americans, [[American Republican Party (1843)|American Republican Party]] (American Nativist Party, American Party), [[Order of the Star Spangled Banner]] (Anti-immigrant secret society)\n| rivals              = [[Dead Rabbits]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Atlantic Guards''' were a 19th-century [[United States|American]] [[street gang]] active in [[New York City]] from the 1840s to the 1860s. It was one of the original, and among the most important gangs of the early days of the [[Bowery]], along with the [[Bowery Boys]], [[American Guards]], [[O'Connell Guards]], and the [[True Blue Americans]].<ref name=\"Asbury\">[[Herbert Asbury|Asbury, Herbert]]. ''The Gangs of New York: An Informal History of the New York Underworld''. New York: Alfred A. Knopf, 1928. (pg. 26-27, 102, 106) {{ISBN|1-56025-275-8}}</ref><ref name=\"Peterson\">Peterson, Virgil W. ''The Mob: 200 Years of Organized Crime in New York''. Ottawa, Illinois: Green Hill Publishers, 1983. (pg. 13) {{ISBN|0-89803-123-0}}</ref><ref name=\"Kenney\">Kenney, Dennis Jay and James O. Finckenauer. ''Organized Crime in America''. New York: Wadsworth Publishing Company, 1995. (pg. 75) {{ISBN|0-534-24702-4}}</ref>\n\nAlthough engaging in [[street fighting]], these gangs were generally less [[street gang|criminal in nature]] than their Five Point rivals, stopping \"just short of murder\",<ref>{{cite news |title=New York Cavalcade: Paid Killers and the Underworld |author=Sobol, Louis |authorlink=Louis Sobol |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=XZstAAAAIBAJ&sjid=u54FAAAAIBAJ&pg=835,3464677 |newspaper=[[Daytona Beach Morning Journal]] |date=November 18, 1965 |accessdate=October 31, 2012}}</ref> instead formed as nativist [[vigilante|vigilante groups]] focused on protecting Bowery neighborhoods.<ref name=\"Giamo\">Giamo, Benedict. ''On the Bowery: Confronting Homelessness in American Society''. Iowa City: University of Iowa Press, 1989. (pg. 9) {{ISBN|0-87745-243-1}}</ref><ref name=\"Sante\">[[Luc Sante|Sante, Luc]]. ''Low Life: Lures and Snares of Old New York''. New York: Farrar, Straus & Giroux, 2003. (pg. 200-203) {{ISBN|0-374-52899-3}}</ref> It was common for Bowery and Five Point gangs alike to imitate (and sometimes parody) actual military companies and wear signature \"uniforms\" (e.g. the [[top hat|stove pipe hats]] and long black [[frock coat]]s of the True Blue Americans).<ref name=\"Asbury\"/><ref name=\"Peterson\"/><ref name=\"Kenney\"/><ref>Kett, Joseph F. ''Rites of Passage: Adolescence in America, 1790 to the Present''. New York: Basic Books, 1977. (pg. 92) {{ISBN|0465070434}}</ref> The Atlantic Guards wore a red stripe on their trousers.<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news |title=Murderous Gangs Of A Half Century And More Ago |author= |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1912/08/04/100591919.pdf |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |date=August 4, 1912 |accessdate=October 31, 2012}}</ref>\n\nA longtime ally of the Bowery Boys, they were referred to by journalist [[Carleton Beals]] as \"[[William Poole|Bill \"the Butcher\" Poole]]'s [[Christopher Street]] thugs\"<ref>[[Carleton Beals|Beals, Carleton]]. ''Brass-Knuckle Crusade: The Great Know-Nothing Conspiracy, 1820-1860''. New York: Hastings House, 1960. (pg. 20)</ref> and often warred with the [[Irish American]] gangs of the [[Five Points, Manhattan|Five Points]], most especially, the [[Dead Rabbits]]. This feud would continue throughout the 1840s and 50s, at the height of the [[Know Nothing]] movement, culminating in the [[Dead Rabbits Riot]] in 1857.<ref name=\"Giamo\"/> The riot originally began with a Five Points raid on No. 42 Bowery, the headquarters of the Bowery Boys and the Atlantic Guards, in \"celebration\" of the [[Fourth of July]].<ref>{{cite news |title=The Gangs of New York: Facts That Out Thrill Fiction |author= |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=12JQAAAAIBAJ&sjid=FA8EAAAAIBAJ&pg=5184,2345188 |newspaper=[[The Milwaukee Sentinel]] |date=November 13, 1928 |accessdate=October 31, 2012}}</ref> The Five Pointers showered the saloon with sticks and paving stone before moving on to the nearby Branch Hotel. The guests managed to hold off the mob until they were driven off by an estimated 300 Atlantic Guards and Bowery Boys.<ref>Ferrara, Eric. ''The Bowery: A History of Grit, Graft and Grandeur''. Charleston, South Carolina: The History Press, 2011. (pg. 50) {{ISBN|1-60949-178-5}}</ref> Fighting continued, however, and soon escalated into a citywide gang war lasting two days before order was restored by the [[New York State Militia]] under Major-General [[Charles W. Sandford]].<ref name=\"Asbury\"/><ref name=\"Sante\"/><ref name=\"NYT\"/><ref>Mendelsohn, Joyce. ''The Lower East Side Remembered and Revisited: A History and Guide to a Legendary New York Neighborhood''. New York: Columbia University Press, 2009. (pg. 238) {{ISBN|0-231-14761-9}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n*The Atlantic Guards are referenced in the [[historical novel]]s ''Andersonville'' (1993) by [[MacKinlay Kantor]] and ''The Coming Storm'' (2011) by Dominic Lagan.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*[[Carleton Beals|Beals, Carleton]]. ''Brass-Knuckle Crusade: The Great Know-Nothing Conspiracy, 1820-1860''. New York: Hastings House, 1960.\n*Harlow, Alvin Fay.