{"title_page": "Bodo Ebhardt", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=April 2020}}\n[[File:Bodo Ebhardt 1912 D\u00fchrkoop.jpg|thumb|upright|Bodo Ebhardt, portrait by [[Rudolf D\u00fchrkoop]], 1912]]\n'''Bodo Heinrich Justus Ebhardt''' (January 5, 1865, [[Bremen]]\u2013February 13, 1945 at [[Marksburg]] near [[Braubach]] was a German [[architect]], [[architectural historian]], castle explorer, and founder and longtime president of the [[German Castles Association]] (''Deutsche Burgenvereinigung'').\n\n==Life==\nEbhardt was the son of Bremen furniture manufacturer and businessman Carl Ebhardt and his wife Agnes (Krollmann) Ebhardt. He attended school in [[Sankt Goarshausen]], where he became fascinated by castles. After graduation he was a commercial apprentice in Magdeburg and Bremen from 1880, but soon gave up this job against the wishes of his parents to self-educate and attended lectures in Berlin. In 1890 he opened his own architectural studio in Berlin. As a castle researcher and restorer, he won the friendship of [[Wilhelm II, German Emperor|Kaiser Wilhelm II]]. He became noted for the reconstruction of numerous castles.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Stein |first1=Rudolf |title=Bremische Biographie : 1912 - 1962 |date=1969 |publisher=Verlag H.M.Hauschild GmbH |location=Bremen |pages=128\u2013130 |language=de |url=http://brema.suub.uni-bremen.de/content/pageview/19219 |accessdate=Jul 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1899 he founded the German Castles Association and from 1909 he lived on the Marksburg in Braubach. Ebhardt was a professor and court architect, in 1909 honorary citizen of Braubach, and in 1928 was a founding member of the Association of Friends of [[Plassenburg]]. He was also a member of the Berlin [[Masonic lodge]] ''Zum Pegasus''.\n\n==Buildings and designs==\n*1892\u20131893: Villa Seibt in Berlin-Grunewald\n*1893\u20131894: Landhaus Ebhardt in Berlin-Grunewald\n*1894: Residential and business complex \"Wilhelmshof\" in Gro\u00df-Lichterfelde near Berlin\n*1894: Log house \"F\u00fcrstenhof\" in Karlshorst near Berlin\n*1894\u20131895: Stable building of the Villa F\u00e4rber in Aachen- Burtscheid\n*1895\u20131896: Schr\u00f6der-Poggelow House in Berlin-Tiergarten\n*1896: Villa Scheche in Berlin Grunewald\n*1896: Ebhardt residence in Berlin-Tiergarten , Rauchstra\u00dfe 13\n*1898: Sports memorial in Berlin, demolished 1973\n*1899\u20131901: Villa Langenscheidt in the \"Alsen Colony\" , Berlin-Wannsee , Colomierstra\u00dfe 1 (stable building added 1902\u20131903)\n*1899\u20131900: Villa Passow/Fulvius/Voss (today Dressler-Verlag) in Heidelberg, Gaisbergstra\u00dfe 55\n*1900\u20131934: Restoration of the Marksburg above Braubach am Rhein\n*1901\u20131908: Restoration of the Hohk\u00f6nigsburg (French [[Haut-K\u0153nigsbourg]]) in [[Alsace]]\n*1901\u20131902: Villa Cornelius Meyer in Berlin-Grunewald\n*1901\u20131902: Reconstruction of the Castle Hohenhaus ([[Herleshausen]])\n*1903: War memorial 1870/71 in Braubach\n*before 1904: Farm building for Villa Martin in Neubabelsberg\n*1904: Villa Remmer in Berlin Grunewald\n*1904\u20131906: Expansion of the Castle Landonvillers in [[Lorraine]]\n*1905\u20131906: Restoration of the church hall of [[Altenburg]] Castle after a fire\n*1906\u20131908: New construction of the Hakeburg in [[Kleinmachnow]]\n*1906\u20131908: Restoration and supplementary buildings at [[Grodziec Castle]]\n*1906\u20131925: Restoration and extension of Neuenstein Palace (Hohenlohe)\n*1908\u20131909: Villa Ribbeck in Berlin-Grunewald\n*1909\u20131925: Restoration and construction of several new buildings at [[Veste Coburg]]\n*before 1910: Haus Lucke in [[Schlettstadt]]\n*1910: Competition design for a Bismarck National Monument on the Elisenh\u00f6he near Bingerbr\u00fcck (not awarded). The monument was never constructed.\n*1911\u20131912: Restoration of [[Sallgast]] Palace\n*1911\u20131913: Expansion of Castle Wommen\n*1912: Restoration of Castle Langenau\n*1912\u20131913: von der Heydt bank headquarters (so-called \"Kleisthaus\") in Berlin, Mauerstra\u00dfe 53\n*1912\u20131914: New construction of the Wartburg-Gasthof in [[Eisenach]]\n*1912\u20131914: Restoration of [[Tzschocha Castle]]\n*1913\u20131914: Restoration and extension of Schloss Gro\u00df Leuthen\n*1913\u20131916: Princely Court Theater in [[Detmold]]\n*1914\u20131915: Expansion of ''Allianz Versicherungs-AG'' in Berlin\n*1914\u20131925: Free reconstruction of the [[Kipfenberg]] Castle\n*1916: Development plan and drafts for the reconstruction of [[Neidenburg]]'s town hall\n*1920: Attempt to restore Neuhausen Palace\n*1920\u20131921: Restoration of [[Kaulsdorf (Saale)|Kaulsdorf]] Castle\n*1920\u20131923: Restoration of Castle Eichicht\n*1921\u20131923: Restoration of [[Scharfenstein Castle (Ore Mountains)|Scharfenstein Castle]] after a fire\n*1921\u20131923: Restoration of [[Creuzburg]] Castle\n*1922\u20131927: New construction of the [[Hornburg]] on existing foundation walls\n*1922\u20131928: Expansion of Heimhof Castle\n*1922\u20131935: Restoration of [[Gr\u00f6ditz]] Castle near [[Wei\u00dfenberg]]\n*1926\u20131927: Petschull House in [[Diez, Germany|Diez]] on the Lahn\n*1929\u20131930: Restoration of the Gollwitz Mansion\n*1931\u20131932: Reconstruction of the Arienfels Palace (''Schloss Arenfels'') near H\u00f6nningen on the Rhine\n*1933\u20131935: New construction of the castle-like Villa M\u00fchlberg in [[Ohrdruf]]\n\n==Publications==\n*{{cite book |last1=Ebhardt |first1=Bodo |title=Die Burgen des Elsass |date=1904 |location=Berlin |language=de|url=https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/011253940 |accessdate=Jul 26, 2019}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Ebhardt |first1=Bodo |title=Steinerne Zeugen: Wehrbauten Veronas |date=1911 |publisher=Burgverlag |location=Berlin-Grunewald | language=de |url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Steinerne-Zeugen-Wehrbauten-Bodo-Ebhardt/dp/B0022TLIBW |accessdate=Jul 25, 2019}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Ebhardt |first1=Bodo |title=Der Schlo\u00dfbau |date=1914 |publisher=Burgverlag |location=Berlin-Grunewald | language=de |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Der_Schlossbau.html?id=V4NZAAAAYAAJ |accessdate=Jul 25, 2019}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Ebhardt |first1=Bodo |title=Krieg und Baukunst in Frankreich und Belgien |date=1915 |publisher=Burgverlag |location=Berlin | language=de |url=https://archive.org/details/kriegundbaukunst00ebhauoft/page/3 |accessdate=Jul 25, 2019}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Ebhardt |first1=Bodo |title=Die Zehn B\u00fccher der Architektur des Vitruv und ihre Herausgegeber seit 1484 |date=1918 |publisher=Burgverlag |location=Berlin |language=de |url=https://archive.org/details/diezehnbcherde00ebhauoft/page/n4 |accessdate=Jul 25, 2019}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Ebhardt |first1=Bodo |title=Deutsche Burgen als Zeugen deutscher Geschichte |date=1925 |publisher=Zillessen |location=Berlin |language=de |url=https://www.amazon.com/Deutsche-Burgen-Zeugen-deutscher-Geschichte/dp/B002JBULV6 |accessdate=Jul 25, 2019}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Ebhardt |first1=Bodo |title=Spanische Burgenfahrt, 1930;  ein Reisebericht |date=1934 |publisher=Burgverlag |location=Marksburg ob Braubach am Rhein |language=de |url=https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/010370555 |accessdate=Jul 26, 2019}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Ebhardt |first1=Bodo |title=Schlo\u00df Arienfels bei H\u00f6nningen am Rhein. Der Bau und seine Geschichte |date=1932 |publisher=Burgverlag |location=Berlin |language=de |url=https://www.booklooker.de/B%C3%BCcher/Angebote/titel=Schlo%C3%9F+Arienfels+bei+H%C3%B6nningen+am+Rhein+-+Der+Bau+und+seine+Geschichte |accessdate=Jul 25, 2019}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Ebhardt |first1=Bodo |title=Burg Trifels: Untersuchungen zur Baugeschichte |date=1938 |publisher=Burgerverlag |language=de |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Burg_Trifels.html?id=74oFPAAACAAJ |accessdate=Jul 26, 2019}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Ebhardt |first1=Bodo |title=Der Wehrbau Europas im Mittelalter |date=1939 |publisher=Deutsche Verlagsgesellschaft |language=de |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Der_Wehrbau_Europas_im_Mittelalter.html?id=Qa1JAQAAIAAJ |accessdate=Jul 26, 2019}}\n\nAn extensive list of the writings critically annotated by [[Ludger Fischer]] can be found in the publication ''Burgenromantik und Burgenrestaurierung um 1900''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Schock-Werner |first1=Barbara (ed.) |last2=von der Dollen |first2=Busso (ed.) |title=Burgenromantik und Burgenrestaurierung um 1900 |date=1999 |publisher=Deutsche Burgenvereinigung |isbn=978-3927558137 |language=de |url=https://www.amazon.de/Burgenromantik-Burgenrestaurierung-1900-Ver%C3%B6ffentlichungen-Burgenvereinigung/dp/3927558133 |accessdate=Jul 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Further reading==\n<!-- Need to wikify remaining citations -->\n*{{cite book |last1=Bekiers |first1=Andreas |title=Bodo Ebhardt 1865-1945: Architekt - Burgenforscher - Restaurator. Leben und Fr\u00fchwerk bis 1900 |date=1984 |language=de |publisher=Verlag Karl-Robert Sch\u00fctze |isbn=978-3928589123 |url=https://www.amazon.de/Bodo-Ebhardt-1865-1945-Burgenforscher-Restaurator/dp/3928589121}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Fischer |first1=Ludger |title=Bodo Ebhardt - Versuche bauk\u00fcnstlerischer Denkmalpflege |date=2010 |language=de |publisher=Deutsche Burgenvereinigung |isbn=978-3927558274 |url=https://www.amazon.de/Bodo-Ebhardt-bauk%C3%BCnstlerischer-Rekonstruktionen-Burgenvereinigung/dp/3927558273}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Fischer |first1=Ludger |title=Bodo Ebhardts Korrekturen der Geschichte |journal=Burgen und Schl\u00f6sser |date=2015 |issue=2 |pages=2\u20137 |language=de |url=https://journals.ub.uni-heidelberg.de/index.php/bus/article/view/49616 |accessdate=Jul 25, 2019}} \n*{{cite journal |last1=Fischer |first1=Ludger |title=Zum 150. Geburtstag von Bodo Ebhardt |journal=Burgen und Schl\u00f6sser |date=2004 |issue=1 |pages=52\u201356 \n |language=de |url=https://journals.ub.uni-heidelberg.de/index.php/bus/article/view/49616/43170 |accessdate=Jul 25, 2019}} \n* Ludger Fischer: ''Das Herrenhaus von der Marwitz in Friedersdorf/Brandenburg. Bodo Ebhardts nicht ausgef\u00fchrte Planungen zur Umgestaltung und Erweiterung des zuvor von Schinkel umgebauten Herrenhauses.'' In: ''Burgen und Schl\u00f6sser.'' 2000/II, S. 83\u201387.\n* Ludger Fischer: ''Die Toranlage von Schlo\u00df Kranichfeld. Ein Bodo Ebhardt-Bau am falschen Platz.'' In: ''Burgen und Schl\u00f6sser.'' 1996/III, S. 126\u2013129.\n* Ludger Fischer: ''Burg Heimhof in der Oberpfalz. Bodo Ebhardts gescheiterte Wohnidee.'' In: ''Burgen und Schl\u00f6sser.'' 1996/II, S. 80\u201385.\n* {{NDB|4|260|261|Ebhardt, Bodo Heinrich Justus|[[Hans Reuther]]|119493357}}\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=nolines widths=\"220px\" heights=\"120px\">\nImage:Kriegerdenkmal Braubach.jpg|Braubach am Rhein: Franco-Prussian war memorial,<br> later also rededicated to the fallen of World War I\nImage:Mohrenstr 62 P1060730 c GS.JPG|Headquarters of Allianz-Versicherung in Berlin (1913\u20131916)\nImage:Berlin Sportdenkmal 1900.jpg|Sportdenkmal Berlin-Gr\u00fcnau\nImage:2016-04-21 15-55-18 haut-koenigsbourg.jpg| View of Hohk\u00f6nigsburg in 2016\nImage:Zamek Czocha front 1.jpg|Tzschocha Castle in 2008\nImage:Hakeburg1.JPG|Die Neue Hakeburg, Kleinmachnow (1906\u20131908)\nImage:Marksburg-Braubach.jpg|The Marksburg from Braubach\nImage:20120704200DR Eichicht (Kaulsdorf Saale) Schlo\u00df Eichicht.jpg|Schloss Eichicht in 2012\nImage:Berlin, Mitte, Mauerstra\u00dfe, Kleisthaus.jpg|Former Kleisthaus headquarters, Berlin Mitte\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ebhardt, Bodo}}\n[[Category:1865 births]]\n[[Category:1945 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century German architects]]\n[[Category:20th-century German architects]]\n[[Category:German architectural historians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Unreferenced|date=July 2019}}\n[[File:Bodo Ebhardt 1912 D\u00fchrkoop.jpg|thumb|upright|Bodo Ebhardt, portrait by [[Rudolf D\u00fchrkoop]], 1912]]\n'''Bodo Heinrich Justus Ebhardt''' (January 5, 1865, [[Bremen]]\u2013February 13, 1945 at [[Marksburg]] near [[Braubach]] was a German [[architect]], [[architectural historian]], castle explorer, and founder and longtime president of the [[German Castles Association]] (''Deutsche Burgenvereinigung'').\n\n==Life==\nEbhardt was the son of Bremen furniture manufacturer and businessman Carl Ebhardt and his wife Agnes (Krollmann) Ebhardt. He attended school in [[Sankt Goarshausen]], where he became fascinated by castles. After graduation he was a commercial apprentice in Magdeburg and Bremen from 1880, but soon gave up this job against the wishes of his parents to self-educate and attended lectures in Berlin. In 1890 he opened his own architectural studio in Berlin. As a castle researcher and restorer, he won the friendship of [[Wilhelm II, German Emperor|Kaiser Wilhelm II]]. He became noted for the reconstruction of numerous castles.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Stein |first1=Rudolf |title=Bremische Biographie : 1912 - 1962 |date=1969 |publisher=Verlag H.M.Hauschild GmbH |location=Bremen |pages=128\u2013130 |lang=de |url=http://brema.suub.uni-bremen.de/content/pageview/19219 |accessdate=Jul 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1899 he founded the German Castles Association and from 1909 he lived on the Marksburg in Braubach. Ebhardt was a professor and court architect, in 1909 honorary citizen of Braubach, and in 1928 was a founding member of the Association of Friends of [[Plassenburg]]. He was also a member of the Berlin [[Masonic lodge]] ''Zum Pegasus''.\n\n==Buildings and designs==\n*1892\u20131893: Villa Seibt in Berlin-Grunewald\n*1893\u20131894: Landhaus Ebhardt in Berlin-Grunewald\n*1894: Residential and business complex \"Wilhelmshof\" in Gro\u00df-Lichterfelde near Berlin\n*1894: Log house \"F\u00fcrstenhof\" in Karlshorst near Berlin\n*1894\u20131895: Stable building of the Villa F\u00e4rber in Aachen- Burtscheid\n*1895\u20131896: Schr\u00f6der-Poggelow House in Berlin-Tiergarten\n*1896: Villa Scheche in Berlin Grunewald\n*1896: Ebhardt residence in Berlin-Tiergarten , Rauchstra\u00dfe 13\n*1898: Sports memorial in Berlin, demolished 1973\n*1899\u20131901: Villa Langenscheidt in the \"Alsen Colony\" , Berlin-Wannsee , Colomierstra\u00dfe 1 (stable building added 1902\u20131903)\n*1899\u20131900: Villa Passow/Fulvius/Voss (today Dressler-Verlag) in Heidelberg, Gaisbergstra\u00dfe 55\n*1900\u20131934: Restoration of the Marksburg above Braubach am Rhein\n*1901\u20131908: Restoration of the Hohk\u00f6nigsburg (French [[Haut-K\u0153nigsbourg]]) in [[Alsace]]\n*1901\u20131902: Villa Cornelius Meyer in Berlin-Grunewald\n*1901\u20131902: Reconstruction of the Castle Hohenhaus ([[Herleshausen]])\n*1903: War memorial 1870/71 in Braubach\n*before 1904: Farm building for Villa Martin in Neubabelsberg\n*1904: Villa Remmer in Berlin Grunewald\n*1904\u20131906: Expansion of the Castle Landonvillers in [[Lorraine]]\n*1905\u20131906: Restoration of the church hall of [[Altenburg]] Castle after a fire\n*1906\u20131908: New construction of the Hakeburg in [[Kleinmachnow]]\n*1906\u20131908: Restoration and supplementary buildings at [[Grodziec Castle]]\n*1906\u20131925: Restoration and extension of Neuenstein Palace (Hohenlohe)\n*1908\u20131909: Villa Ribbeck in Berlin-Grunewald\n*1909\u20131925: Restoration and construction of several new buildings at [[Veste Coburg]]\n*before 1910: Haus Lucke in [[Schlettstadt]]\n*1910: Competition design for a Bismarck National Monument on the Elisenh\u00f6he near Bingerbr\u00fcck (not awarded). The monument was never constructed.\n*1911\u20131912: Restoration of [[Sallgast]] Palace\n*1911\u20131913: Expansion of Castle Wommen\n*1912: Restoration of Castle Langenau\n*1912\u20131913: von der Heydt bank headquarters (so-called \"Kleisthaus\") in Berlin, Mauerstra\u00dfe 53\n*1912\u20131914: New construction of the Wartburg-Gasthof in [[Eisenach]]\n*1912\u20131914: Restoration of [[Tzschocha Castle]]\n*1913\u20131914: Restoration and extension of Schloss Gro\u00df Leuthen\n*1913\u20131916: Princely Court Theater in [[Detmold]]\n*1914\u20131915: Expansion of ''Allianz Versicherungs-AG'' in Berlin\n*1914\u20131925: Free reconstruction of the [[Kipfenberg]] Castle\n*1916: Development plan and drafts for the reconstruction of [[Neidenburg]]'s town hall\n*1920: Attempt to restore Neuhausen Palace\n*1920\u20131921: Restoration of [[Kaulsdorf (Saale)|Kaulsdorf]] Castle\n*1920\u20131923: Restoration of Castle Eichicht\n*1921\u20131923: Restoration of [[Scharfenstein Castle (Ore Mountains)|Scharfenstein Castle]] after a fire\n*1921\u20131923: Restoration of [[Creuzburg]] Castle\n*1922\u20131927: New construction of the [[Hornburg]] on existing foundation walls\n*1922\u20131928: Expansion of Heimhof Castle\n*1922\u20131935: Restoration of [[Gr\u00f6ditz]] Castle near [[Wei\u00dfenberg]]\n*1926\u20131927: Petschull House in [[Diez, Germany|Diez]] on the Lahn\n*1929\u20131930: Restoration of the Gollwitz Mansion\n*1931\u20131932: Reconstruction of the Arienfels Palace (''Schloss Arenfels'') near H\u00f6nningen on the Rhine\n*1933\u20131935: New construction of the castle-like Villa M\u00fchlberg in [[Ohrdruf]]\n\n==Publications==\n*{{cite book |last1=Ebhardt |first1=Bodo |title=Die Burgen des Elsass |date=1904 |location=Berlin |lang=de|url=https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/011253940 |accessdate=Jul 26, 2019}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Ebhardt |first1=Bodo |title=Steinerne Zeugen: Wehrbauten Veronas |date=1911 |publisher=Burgverlag |location=Berlin-Grunewald | lang=de |url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Steinerne-Zeugen-Wehrbauten-Bodo-Ebhardt/dp/B0022TLIBW |accessdate=Jul 25, 2019}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Ebhardt |first1=Bodo |title=Der Schlo\u00dfbau |date=1914 |publisher=Burgverlag |location=Berlin-Grunewald | lang=de |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Der_Schlossbau.html?id=V4NZAAAAYAAJ |accessdate=Jul 25, 2019}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Ebhardt |first1=Bodo |title=Krieg und Baukunst in Frankreich und Belgien |date=1915 |publisher=Burgverlag |location=Berlin | lang=de |url=https://archive.org/details/kriegundbaukunst00ebhauoft/page/3 |accessdate=Jul 25, 2019}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Ebhardt |first1=Bodo |title=Die Zehn B\u00fccher der Architektur des Vitruv und ihre Herausgegeber seit 1484 |date=1918 |publisher=Burgverlag |location=Berlin |lang=de |url=https://archive.org/details/diezehnbcherde00ebhauoft/page/n4 |accessdate=Jul 25, 2019}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Ebhardt |first1=Bodo |title=Deutsche Burgen als Zeugen deutscher Geschichte |date=1925 |publisher=Zillessen |location=Berlin |lang=de |url=https://www.amazon.com/Deutsche-Burgen-Zeugen-deutscher-Geschichte/dp/B002JBULV6 |accessdate=Jul 25, 2019}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Ebhardt |first1=Bodo |title=Spanische Burgenfahrt, 1930;  ein Reisebericht |date=1934 |publisher=Burgverlag |location=Marksburg ob Braubach am Rhein |lang=de |url=https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/010370555 |accessdate=Jul 26, 2019}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Ebhardt |first1=Bodo |title=Schlo\u00df Arienfels bei H\u00f6nningen am Rhein. Der Bau und seine Geschichte |date=1932 |publisher=Burgverlag |location=Berlin |lang=de |url=https://www.booklooker.de/B%C3%BCcher/Angebote/titel=Schlo%C3%9F+Arienfels+bei+H%C3%B6nningen+am+Rhein+-+Der+Bau+und+seine+Geschichte |accessdate=Jul 25, 2019}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Ebhardt |first1=Bodo |title=Burg Trifels: Untersuchungen zur Baugeschichte |date=1938 |publisher=Burgerverlag |lang=de |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Burg_Trifels.html?id=74oFPAAACAAJ |accessdate=Jul 26, 2019}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Ebhardt |first1=Bodo |title=Der Wehrbau Europas im Mittelalter |date=1939 |publisher=Deutsche Verlagsgesellschaft |lang=de |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Der_Wehrbau_Europas_im_Mittelalter.html?id=Qa1JAQAAIAAJ |accessdate=Jul 26, 2019}}\n\nAn extensive list of the writings critically annotated by [[Ludger Fischer]] can be found in the publication ''Burgenromantik und Burgenrestaurierung um 1900''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Schock-Werner |first1=Barbara (ed.) |last2=von der Dollen |first2=Busso (ed.) |title